Dhritarashtra said: O mighty-armed Yudhisthira, are you all right? Accompanied by all his brothers citizens and villagers
I hope those who follow you are also well O king your ministers servants and preceptors
I hope they too live in your country without fear I trust you are following the ancient way of life attended by royal sages
I hope your treasury is filled without breaking the law You behave accordingly to your friends in the midst of your enemies
You do not see the brahmins or the graharas properly O best of the Bharatas I hope they will be satisfied with your conduct Where are the enemies, citizens, servants or relatives? O best of kings are you performing sacrifices faithful to the gods of your ancestors
O Bharatha, do you worship with guest food and drink? I hope the brahmins are engaged in their own duties on the path of justice
Kshatriyas or Vaishyas or Sudras of family. I hope your wife children and the elderly do not grieve or beg for you O best of men I hope the sons-in-law are worshiped in your house
I hope this royal saintly dynasty has come to you as king As it should be, O great king, he does not despair of fame. The jurist replied to him who spoke thus
