King Yudhisthira alone pursued him. He entered the terrible forest and sometimes he could not be seen.
O Vidura, O king, I am your beloved Yudhisthira. Having said this the king rushed towards him with great effort
Then the best of the wise stood in a secluded solitude. I hope Vidura is taking refuge in a tree in the middle of the forest
The king showed him only his figure, which was very emaciated. Highly intelligent Yudhisthira recognized him
Yudhisthira, saying, "I am," stood in front. On hearing this the king paid homage to Vidura
Then he looked at the king without blinking Vidura fixed his gaze on him with concentrated gaze
The intelligent Vidura entered with his limbs and his limbs. He placed the life-force in the life-force and the senses in the senses.
By the power of yoga he entered the body of the king Vidura seemed to be blazing with the effulgence of the king of righteousness
Vidura's body was still stunned. Then the king beheld him unconscious lying under a tree
He felt strong and multiplied himself then. The effulgent king of righteousness, Arjuna, remembered that. O lord he knew everything about himself among the citizens The Dharma of Yoga as declared by the effulgent Vyasa.
Then the king of righteousness wanted to perform the funeral rites there Desiring to burn him the learned Ravana spoke these words O king this Vidura should not be burnt This is your eternal duty to keep your body here
