Vaiśampāyana said O best of the Bhrigus the learned sage approached him in anger and thoughtfully said 'Alas seated on the bull's parvana'
O king unrighteousness does not immediately bear fruit like a cow Slowly weaving it cuts the roots of the doer.
If he does not see himself in his sons or daughters Sin is certainly rewarded just as if eaten by a preceptor in the stomach
That which he placed as the brahmin Kachamangirasa then. He was of sinless conduct knower of dharma and devoted to service in my house
The killing of him and the killing of my daughter "O bull festival listen to this I shall leave you and your relatives O king I cannot stay with you in your kingdom
"O demon you know me to be a liar As you do not control this fault of yours you are neglecting it
Vrishaparva said: I know neither iniquity nor lies in you, O Bhrigu. Righteousness and truth are in you Please be pleased with us If you leave us and go away from here, O Bhrigu. We shall enter the sea There is no other refuge
Venus said, "Enter the sea or the directions, you demons. I am capable of bearing my beloved daughter for she is my beloved
O Devayani please be merciful to me wherever I am alive I am the protector of Yoga for thee, as Brihaspati is for Indra.
Vrishaparva said O Bhrigu whatever wealth the kings of the asuras have You are his lord on earth elephants cows and horses and mine
Venus said: O great demon whatever wealth there is of the kings of the demons If I am his lord this Devayani please be gracious to me
Vaishampayana said Thus addressed, the great poet Vrishaparva replied, "So be it. Bhrigu approached Devayani and addressed her
Devayani said O dear son of Bhrigu if you are the lord of the king's wealth I do not know about it let the king himself tell you
Vrishaparva said O goddess with a pure smile whatever desire you desire Even if it is rare I shall give it to you
Devayani said the maidservant I desire Sharmishta with a thousand maidens Let her follow me wherever my father gives her
Vrishaparva said Get up and go and fetch Sharmistha quickly And may Devayani fulfill whatever he desires
Vaishampayana said Then the midwife went there and spoke to Sharmistha O gentle lady arise and bring happiness to your kinsmen
Encouraged by Devayani the brahmin abandons his disciples O sinless one you should fulfill his desire in the evening
Sharmistha said I shall fulfill her desire today If Venus calls me like this I will be made Devayani Let not Venus and Devayani go away for my sake because of my fault
Vaishampayana said Then the palanquin was surrounded by a thousand maidens At the command of her father she left the best of cities at once
Sharmistha said I am your maidservant with a thousand maidservants I shall follow you wherever your father will give you
Devayānī said: When you praised me, I became your daughter, and when you asked for it, I accepted it. How can you become a maidservant daughter of one who is being praised
Sharmistha said by whatever means one can bring happiness to one's afflicted relatives Therefore I shall follow you wherever your father will give you
Vaishampayana said: In the assembly of servants promised by the daughter of Vrishaparva O best among kings Devayani said to her father
Devayani said O dear best of brahmins I am entering the city I am satisfied Thy wisdom and the strength of knowledge are infallible.
Vaishampayana said Thus addressed by his daughter the illustrious best of brahmins Having been worshiped by all the demons he entered the city in delight
Vaishampayana said: As the great Pandavas had departed, groaning. Draupadi sat down to walk on foot
Tired and overwhelmed with grief by the wind and rain The ascetic Panchali was deluded by her tenderness
She trembled with her arms and dark eyes in delusion She clung to her thighs with her rounded arms
They were like elephants with their thighs hanging down. Suddenly she fell down on the ground trembling like a banana tree
She was falling down like a creeper with a beautiful hip being broken. Valiant Nakula rushed at him and seized him
Nakula said O king this darkeyed daughter of the king of Panchal Exhausted she fell down on the ground Behold her, O Arjuna.
She is soft-spoken and does not deserve suffering but will suffer greatly O great king console this exhausted lady
Vaishampayana said The king was greatly grieved at his words Bhima and Sahadeva rushed at once
But Kaunteya looked at her with a pale and emaciated face. The righteous Rama took him on his lap and lamented in distress
Yudhisthira said How is it that she should lie on her own spread in secret houses? The beautiful lady of beautiful complexion is lying down on the ground in distress
How delicate are your feet and how your face is like a lotus Today for my sake the noble lady has turned dark
What have I done this foolishly for the sake of gambling He took Krishna with him while he was wandering in the forest teeming with deer
You will find happiness, O auspicious one, having found the Pandavas as your husbands. Thus the largeeyed lady was given to her by her father the king of miserable footsteps
Exhausted by fatigue and grief I cannot attain all that She is lying on the ground fallen down because of my sinful actions
Vaishampayana said: Thus, while Yudhisthira, the king of righteousness, was lamenting. All the best of brahmins headed by Dhaumya arrived there
They consoled him and worshiped him with their blessings They chanted mantras and performed rituals for the killing of demons
While the mantras were being recited by the great sages for peace. Touched again and again by the cold hands of the Pandavas.
She was served with cold air mixed with water Panchali slowly regained her composure having attained happiness
He took hold of that wretched black woman on an invincible bed The sons of Partha rested the ascetic who had regained consciousness
Her feet with red soles were characteristic of worship They carried him slowly with their hands born of worms
