The hunter said, "It is better to be found than to be found. But the gain of time which may be true will not be yours in this vile world.
Gautama said: What is the attainment by taking and killing the enemy? What is the attainment of desire by attaining and not releasing the enemy? O gentle serpent why should I not forgive us or for what reason should I not act for our liberation
The hunter said: Many should be protected from this one, and not one from many, Gautama. Those who know righteousness forsake an offender Kill this sinful reptile
Gautama said O hunter my son will not be found alive in this slain serpent I do not see any other virtue in killing him Therefore O serpent hunter let him live
The hunter said: Having killed Vritra, the king of the gods offered the best part of the sacrifice and obtained his share. O trident O god follow the path of the gods Kill the serpent at once Let there be no doubt about it
Bhishma said, Though Gautama was repeatedly addressed to the serpent. The most fortunate lady did not contemplate the sinful hunter The serpent, breathing heavily, restrained himself with difficulty. Tormented by the noose he uttered a soft human voice
The serpent said, "What is my fault, O foolish Arjuna?" Death whispered to me helplessly that I was not free
He was bitten by his words neither out of anger nor out of lust O greedy one if there is any sin he commits
The hunter said If you have done this evil serpent under the control of someone else That is why you are guilty of this
For in the action of an earthen vessel, as in the case of rods and wheels. They are assumed to be the cause and so are you, O serpent.
The serpent said, "You are a sinful serpent and you are to be killed by me. O serpent you are explaining yourself as the reason for this All these are under their own control, as are the rods and wheels. So do I. Therefore I do not think it is your fault.
Or do you think they are also mutually exclusive? Doubt of cause and effect arises from mutual encouragement.
In this case I am not guilty I am not to be killed nor am I guilty If you think that there is a sin in the combination, it is a sin.
The hunter said If there were no cause you would not be the doer You are the cause of destruction Therefore I think you should be killed
Even if it is untrue, the work is not covered here by the serpent. Therefore there is no reason to kill him here alone Why do you think so much
The serpent said: In the absence of action there is no action, even in the cause of truth and truth. Therefore, in this same cause, let me explain the cause in particular.
Another may be guilty of destroying animals in the experiment If I am considered to be the cause of the hunter in fact.
The hunter said O foolish one you are to be killed you are a cruel murderer of children O vile serpent why are you talking so much about being killed again
The serpent said: Just as a greedy Karvija offers oblations in sacrifice They obtain no fruit here in the combination of fruits and so do I.
Bhishma said Thus speaking, the serpent was driven to death. Then death arrived and said to the serpent
Death said O serpent prompted by time I have whispered to you I am not the cause of his destruction nor am I the creature of the child
Just as the wind blows the water bodies here and there Like a serpent in the water I am under the control of time
The Sattvic, the Rajasic, and the Tamasic, and whatever else. All beings of the nature of time act in beings.
movable and immovable, whether in heaven or on earth. All serpents are of time; this world is of time.
And the instincts in this world, and so also the renunciations. Their distortions and whatever else is said to be of time.
The sun, the moon, Vishnu, the water, the wind and the hundred sacrifices. Agni: his own earth, Mitra, Parjanya, Vasu and Aditi
O serpent the river and the ocean are both emotions and absences All things are created and taken away again and again by time. Knowing this, how can you think me a faulty snake? And yet you are also guilty of me in this milk.
The serpent said: Whether you are innocent or guilty I do not tell you to die I am telling you that you encouraged me
But if there is a fault in time, it will be taken there too. There is no fault in me We are not authorized to do this
I must relieve you of this fault in any way My purpose here is that there would be no fault even in death.
Bhishma said Then the serpent said to Arjuna: I have heard the words of death. You should torture me with a rope for various sins
The hunter said O serpent I have heard the words of death and yours O serpent there is nothing wrong with you
Death and you are the reason for the destruction of this child. I think both are the cause, not the cause and the causeless.
And damnation, the evil-minded, the cruel, the painful to the virtuous. Sinful cause of sin I shall also kill you
Death said, "We are cows, forced by time, to do what is directed. If you can see properly the boats should go by fault
The hunter said, "If you are both subject to time, you are my death serpents. I wish to know the nature of joy and anger
Death said, "Any action that may be taken is all prompted by time. O hunter I have already said this from time immemorial Therefore both of us are determined by time O hunter you should never go to the boats by any fault
Bhishma said: Then the time came, in that doubt of righteousness and wealth. Death said to the greedy serpent and to Arjuna.
Time said, "I am not, nor is this death, the hunter of the serpent. We are not the cause of the death of a sinful creature
The action which he did, O Arjuna, is our inducement. There is no other cause for his destruction He is being killed by his own actions
He died for the action he had taken. This action is the cause of destruction We are all subject to action
The world of karma-dayadavan is characterized by the relationship of karma. They encourage actions here as we encourage each other
as the potter makes from the clay whatever he pleases. Thus man attains to the action performed by himself.
As the two shadows are always well connected constantly. Similarly, action and the doer are bound together by their own actions.
Thus I am not, nor is the death serpent, nor are you. This old brahmin woman is not the only reason for this
O King while he was thus speaking a brahmin named Gautami Considering the worlds to be convinced of his own actions, he said to Arjuna.
Gautama said Neither time nor the serpent nor death is the cause here. In due course of time this young boy died due to his own actions
I have done the deed that caused my son to die Let time pass and death, O Arjuna, release the serpent.
Bhishma said Then death and time and the serpent went away as they had come. Arjuna was without grief and Gautama was without grief.
On hearing this, O king, be at peace and do not be grief-stricken. O King everyone goes to the worlds according to the consequences of their own actions
Neither you nor Duryodhana has done this. Know that this was done by time which killed the kings
Vaishampayana said: Hearing these words, he became relieved of his fever. Effulgent Yudhisthira conversant with righteousness inquired
I must tell you this, O best of men. O lord of men for what purpose have I come here to cut you off
O lord of men this is the daily sacrifice of the Kshatriyas of the Bhrigus They will also go to separation due to fateful reasons
And the kshatriyas will kill all the Bhrigus, O lord of men. Tormented by the punishment of fate they were torn from the womb
Then there will arise in our family an increase of the clan There was a mighty Urva who shone like the blazing Sun
He will cause the fire of wrath to destroy the three worlds Who will reduce the earth with its mountains and forests to ashes
He will put out the fire for a while The foremost of ascetics threw the vadavaka into the sea
O great king he had a son named Richika the delight of Bhrigu O sinless one the entire art of archery will be presented directly For the absence of Kshatriyas for a fateful reason. He will accept him and pass him on to his son Jamadagni, the most fortunate, the self-conscious by austerities. That tiger among Bhrigus too will hold that Veda
O righteous one he will marry a daughter from your family O best of kings it is to revive your dynasty
The great ascetic obtained the daughter of Gadhi and your granddaughter She will beget a son who will be a brahmin and a kshatriya
A kshatriya performing brahmin rituals is like Brihaspati in prowess In your dynasty Viswamitra is the virtuous son of Gadhi
O effulgent one he will bestow upon you what is endowed with great austerities The women will be the reason for that change
This will not happen other than by the command of my grandfather In the third person you will attain brahminhood And you will be related to the Bhrigus, the self-realized souls.
Bhishma replied to the words of the great sage Cyavana The king was delighted to hear these words
Again, the king of men. The king urged him to seek a boon and said O great sage yes I shall do whatever you desire
Let the effulgent Cyavana become a brahmin and let his mind be fixed on righteousness Thus addressed, the sage Cyavana replied, "So be it. Having obtained the king's permission he proceeded on a pilgrimage I have told you all this in full, O king. The cause of the relationship between the Bhrigus and the Kusikas.
O king it happened as the sage had predicted The birth of Rama and sage Viswamitra
Yudhisthira said: Thou art such in this world, well versed in the Vedas and the limbs of the Vedas. Tell me what action will lead to the supreme destination
The serpent said: Giving it to the vessel, saying the dear things, and speaking the truth, O Bharatha. I think that one who is engaged in nonviolence will go to heaven
Yudhisthira said: Why is the Guru seen by charity or by the serpent or by truth? Tell me what is heavy and light about nonviolence and unpleasantness
The serpent said: Charity, truth, truth, non-violence and pleasure. Heavy and light are seen because of the importance of these tasks
For some reason, truth is superior to charity. O Indra among kings charity is better than truthfulness
Thus, O great archer, pleasant words, O king. Non-violence is seen as grave and therefore pleasant.
This is how it will be, O king, after the action is required. Tell me whatever else you wish till I tell you
Yudhisthira said How is the serpent's destination in heaven and the sure fruit of his actions Tell me about my disembodied objects
The serpent said O king the movements of Tiga have been observed by their own actions That which is human, the abode of heaven and the birth of animals is threefold.
There he was lazy in giving charity and other things from the world of men He attains heaven for reasons consistent with the purpose of non-violence.
And for the opposite reasons, O king, he becomes a human being. O dear I shall also describe the distinction between animals and animals
He is full of lust and anger and is full of violence and greed. Deviated from humanity, he is born in the womb of an animal.
The separation of animals and women is prescribed for the sake of man. Divinity is also seen in cows and other animals and also in horses.
That is these movements, my dear, the creature moves and works. A brahmin always establishes himself in greatness
Born and born and enjoys strongly, that soul is embodied. O dear I have been satisfied with the desire to rule the subjects for the sake of fruition
Yudhisthira said: In sound, touch and form, as well as in taste and smell. O serpent tell me exactly where he lives
Why doesn't he take objects simultaneously, O great one? O best of serpents tell me everything I have said
The serpent said: That which is the self-matter, O long-lived one, is attached to the body. He enjoys the pleasures of the senses in accordance with tradition.
Here also is knowledge, intellect and mind, O best of the Bharatas. Learn from me the means of obtaining his enjoyment
The mind, my dear, passes through these objects one by one. For the Self of beings, dwelling in the abode of objects, is situated in the field.
Even there, O tiger among men, the mind of the living being is prescribed. Therefore, it is not possible to grasp it here simultaneously.
That soul, O tiger among men, rests between the eyebrows. It creates intellect in various objects, high and low.
And the pain of the buddheshttarakala is seen by the wise. O tiger among kings this is the method of the knower of the field
Yudhisthira said: Tell me the supreme characteristic of the mind and the intellect. This is the supreme duty prescribed for those who know the Self.
The serpent said Intelligence follows the self, my dear, and is prescribed by calamity. For this intellect, dependent on that, becomes his seeker.
Intelligence arises from action, for the mind arises from action. By the prescription of the alities of intellect the mind becomes like that alth.
This is the adjective, my dear, which is the difference between the mind and the intellect. You too are enlightened here How do you think
Yudhisthira said: Oh, best of the wise, this is your auspicious intelligence. Why do you inquire about what is known and should be known
How did delusion enter you, the omniscient, the inhabitant of heaven? I have great doubts that he performed such wonderful deeds
The serpent said: Even a man of good intelligence is deluded by wealth if he is brave. It is my opinion that everyone who is living in happiness is deluded
That I, O Yudhisthira, am possessed by the delusion of wealth. I fell down and woke up but I will awaken you
O great king you have done a good deed to me O scorcher of enemies The curse has been exhausted and it has been very difficult for me after you have spoken to me with a saintly man.
I used to fly in a divine plane in heaven Intoxicated with pride I thought of nothing else
Brahmarshis gods gandharvas yakshas rakshasas and serpents All the inhabitants of the three worlds offer their hands to me
The creature I see with my eyes, O lord of the earth. I quickly dispel his splendor That is the strength of my sight
He carried my palanquin with seventeen brahmarshis O king that deprivation of my fortune has destroyed me
There I touched the sage Agastya carrying him on foot Then Agastya said to me 'You too will become a serpent'
Then he fell from that aerial chariot with the signs of a fall As he fell he realized that he had become a serpent and his face was turned downwards I asked the brahmin to put an end to the curse
The serpent said O lord forgive me for being confused by my negligence Then he said to me as I was falling down compassionately
Yudhisthira, the king of righteousness, will deliver you from the curse. O lord of men this is a terrible and sinful act of pride
O great king when the fruits are exhausted you will attain the meritorious fruits Then I was astonished to see the power of his austerities
Brahman and Brahminhood by which I have sucked you. Truthfulness, restraint, austerity, charity, nonviolence and steadfastness in irreligion.
The seekers are always men, neither caste nor clan, O king. Arishta is this mighty brother of Bhimasena O great king may you be well I shall go back to heaven
Vaishampayana said Having said this, king Nahusha released his body from the dragon. Having assumed a divine body he ascended to heaven
Even the righteous Yudhisthira accompanied by his brother Bhima. The illustrious Rama accompanied by Dhaumya returned to the hermitage
They then told all the brahmins assembled in the same manner. Yudhisthira king of all dharmas narrated that story
All the brahmins and his three brothers heard this O king the illustrious Draupadi was very ashamed
But all of them, the best of brahmins, desired the welfare of the Pandavas. Condemning Bhima's audacity they said 'No'
The Pandavas, however, beholding the mighty Bhima, freed from fear. They cheered and laughed with joy
Sanjaya said: Equally in the army of the greatest, they did not retreat. All of them, devoted to the world of Brahma, attained it, O Arjuna. Not equipped with a slightly smaller package. The chariots were not accompanied by charioteers nor were foot soldiers accompanied by infantry
The horses did not fight with the horses nor the elephants with the fighters of the elephants O great king there they fight like madmen, O Arjuna. There was a great and dreadful confrontation between the armies of men and elephants scattered everywhere
In that great and terrible decay there was no distinction Then also Shalya, Kripa and Chitrasena, O Arjuna. Duryodhana and Vikarna rode in bright chariots The valiant men of the Pandavas shook the banner in the battle.
That Pandu army was being killed in battle by the great men. O king like a boat in the water it is whirled about by the wind in many ways
Because the winter time cuts the marrow of the cows. Similarly, Bhishma cuts the hearts of the sons of Pandu. Similarly by your army and by the great Partha. Elephants resembling nine clouds fell down in great numbers
And the leaders of men are seen being crushed by Partha. They were shot with thousands of arrows and darts
The huge elephants fell down making a terrible sound in distress The great souls who were killed on duty were deprived of their ornaments Hidden Mayodhan shone with his heads and earrings. O great king it was at the time of the destruction of the best of great heroes
Bhishma, the mighty warrior, and the Pandavas, Arjuna. O king they saw their grandfather defeated in battle All those sons turned around, rewarded by the army. Wishing death in battle they made heaven their refuge
The Pandavas turned to that heroic destroyer. Even the Pandavas, O great king, remembering various things.
O lord of men you and your son have suffered in the past The valiant men abandoned fear in battle and were devoted to the world of Brahma
They are fighting your sons and daughters as if they were happy. The great charioteer commander of the army addressed the army in the battle
The Somas with the Srinjayas attacked the Ganges. On hearing the words of the commander of the army the sons of Srinjaya were united
Struck by the shower of arrows they rushed towards the Ganges O king your father Shantanava was about to be killed
Overcome with anger he fought the Srinjayas. O dear Rama was famous for his fame in the past
The weapons training imparted is destructive to the enemy. Following that instruction he destroyed the enemy's army
Day by day the grandfather of the Kurus grew old among the Parthians Bhishma the slayer of enemy heroes killed ten thousand men
O best of the Bharatas on the tenth day Bhishma alone in the battle with the fishes and the Panchalas.
Seven great charioteers were killed killing an elephant and a horse Having killed five thousand chariots Rama the great grandsire
and fourteen thousand men in the great battle. There were also thousands of tusks and tens of thousands of horses
O lord your father did not do it by the strength of his teaching Then he destroyed all the kings and Varuthi
Virata's beloved brother Satanika has been killed And having slain in battle a hundred soldiers, the mighty Bhishma.
O great king the king threw down thousands of them with his spears The warriors in battle, anxious, cry out to Arjuna.
And those who were some of the Parthians who attacked Arjuna. The kings reached Bhishma and went to the abode of Yama Thus Bhishma with networks of arrows all around in ten directions. Having crossed the army of the Parthas he stood at the head of the army
On the tenth day he performed a great feat He stood between the two armies holding his bow and arrows O king none of the kings were able to look at him
It was as if the Sun had reached the middle of summer and was scorching in the sky as he might have tormented the army of demons in battle.
Thus did Bhishma, the son of the Pandavas, torment him, O Arjuna. And so, seeing him overpowered, Madhusoodana.
The son of Devakī, pleased, said to Arjuna. This Shantanava Bhishma is standing between the two armies.
Slay them with force and you will have victory Stop him by force where this army is breaking up.
For no one else, O lord, can bear the arrows of Bhishma. Then at that moment the monkey flag was raised by the king
With his arrows he hid Bhishma with his flag and chariot and horse That bull also attacked the chiefs of the Kurus and the Pandavas. He chased them in many ways with a barrage of arrows Then the king of Panchala and the mighty Dhrishtaketu.
The Pandavas and Bhimasena and Dhrishtadyumna were his attendants. The Yamas Chekitana and five Kekayas were also killed
Then mightyarmed Satyaki and Saubhadra and Ghatotkacha The sons of Draupadi, Sikhandi and the mighty Kuntibhoja. Susharma and Virata, the mighty sons of the Pandavas. These and many others were tormented by the arrows of Bhishma.
They were plunged into the ocean of sorrow by Arjuna when they were lifted up Then Shikhandi quickly grabbed the supreme weapon. Protected by his crown he ran towards Bhishma alone
Then he killed all his followers who knew the division of battle. Frighteningly defeated he ran towards Bhishma alone Satyaki and Chekitana and Dhrishtadyumna were his attendants.
Virata and also Drupada, the two sons of Madri, the Pandavas. The horses fled to Bhishma alone protected by a strong bowman
Abhimanyu and Draupadi's five sons in battle. They ran to Bhishma in battle with their great weapons ready.
They all armed with strong bows and did not flee in battles Many times Bhishma was stabbed and wounded.
Shooting away the hosts of arrows released by the best of kings The wretched soul of the Pandavas sank into the Varuthi.
As if playing the grandsire Rama shot an arrow He did not approach Panchali, smiling again and again.
Remembering his femininity, Bhishma offered him to the breaker of arrows and shields. The great charioteer rode seven chariots in the army of Drupada.
Then instantly there was a resounding sound Matsya Panchala and Chedi rushed at him alone
O scorcher of enemies they followed men horses chariots and trails Like clouds covering the sun they covered him alone
Bhishma, the son of Bhagirathi, scorching the enemies in battle. Then there was a battle between them and the gods and demons Bhishma with his crown arrived with Sikhandi in front of him
Dhritarashtra said: Whose warriors are fighting there in front of them, delighted, O Sanjaya? Who are these who are proud of their minds and who are they who are wretched and unconscious
Who struck first there in the heart-shaking battle. Whether they are mine or the Pandavas, tell me, O Sanjaya.
Whose army is the source of the fragrant flowers? The words and circumambulations of the warriors roared
Sanjaya said Then the warriors of both the armies were defeated. The garlands of fragrant flowers are equal in both places O best of the Bharatas of the assembled armies. There was a tremendous friction caused by the collision
The sound of musical instruments was tumultuous mixed with conches and drums The brave warriors roared at each other. O king there was a great difference between the two armies
The warriors looked at each other, O best of the Bharatas. Let the elephants roar and the armies rejoice
Vaishampayana said: At this very time, however, Bhimasena was also a mighty warrior. Having attained the dust of righteousness he proceeded towards the eastern direction
He crushed foreign nations with a great wheel of force The mighty Ravana was bitten by a demon full of elephants horses and chariots The tiger of Bharata was surrounded, increasing the grief of his enemies. The tiger among men reached the great city of Panchalas
The Pandavas consoled the Panchalas by various means. Then that mighty Rama the best among the Bharatas crossed the Ganges and Videha In a short time the lord conquered the Dasarna There king Sudharma of Dasarna was hair-raising He fought a great unarmed battle with Bhimasena
Bhimasena, however, saw the action of the great man. He made the mighty Sudharma commander of his army
Then Bhima of terrible prowess proceeded in the eastern direction O king with his mighty army he seemed to be shaking the earth
O king he saw the lord of the horse sacrifices pleasing with his followers Heroic Rama the foremost among the strong won the battle with his prowess
That Arjuna, having defeated him, did not do so by a very severe action. O descendant of the Kurus the mighty warrior conquered the eastern region
Then turn south to the great city of Pulinda. He brought the delicate king Sumitra under his control
Then by the command of the king of righteousness the best of the Bharatas Janamejaya approached the mighty Sisupala
The king of Chedi also heard of the intention of the Pandavas. O scorcher of enemies I came out of the city and received him
O great king the two bulls Kuruchedi then met They inquired about the prowess of both their relatives
Then the king of Chedi reported the kingdom to the lord Laughing he said to Bhima O sinless one what are you doing
Bhima then informed him of the intention of the king of righteousness The king accepted him and did as he was told
O king Bhima stayed there for thirteen nights Honored by Sisupala Rama with his army departed
Having offered obeisances to Narayana and Nara the best of men Then goddess Saraswati should chant Jaya to Vyasa
Sanjaya said Then the heroes accompanied by them proceeded southward They arrived at the camp at the time of sunset
Then they hurriedly released their horses and became frightened They reached a deep place and entered it in disguise
They stood not far from the army encampment They were cut down with sharp weapons and bruised from all sides He took a deep and hot breath and thought like a Pandava.
And hearing the dreadful roar of the Pandavas, eager for victory. Accordingly, frightened, they fled again, facing east.
They left in a moment tired and thirsty The great archers could not bear it and were overcome with anger. Tormented by the death of the king they stood still for a moment
Dhritarashtra said: This is an unbelievable act committed by Bhima, O Sanjaya. That my son with the life of a thousand elephants has been thrown down
He is invincible and young like the thunderbolt of all beings My son is slain by the Pandavas in battle, O Sanjaya. It is not possible for men in a herd of cows to overcome destiny That my son was thrown down by the paths in the battle Surely my heart is full of the essence of the mountains, O Sanjaya. On hearing that one hundred sons had been killed it was not torn into a thousand pieces How can an old couple have a murdered son? I do not wish to dwell in the country of the Arjuna.
How can you be the father of a king and the king himself, O Sanjaya? I shall proceed as a messenger by the command of the Pandavas.
Having commanded the whole earth, Sanjaya stood on his head. How can I become a messenger today who is inevitable
How can I hear the words of Bhima, O Sanjaya? He killed my hundred sons in one single stroke
The words of that great Vidura have come true By not carrying out the words of my son, O Sanjaya.
My dear son Duryodhana was killed by unrighteousness What did Kritavarma, Kripa and Draupadi do, O Sanjaya?
Sanjaya said: O king the Tawakas have gone and are not far away They beheld a dreadful forest covered with various trees and creepers
They rested for a moment and the best of the horses got water. At sunset they reached a vast forest
It is inhabited by herds of various animals and surrounded by flocks of various birds It was covered with various trees and creepers and inhabited by various serpents
It is filled with various waters and decorated with various flowers It was covered with hundreds of lotuses and full of blue lilies
They entered the dreadful forest and looked around There they beheld a banyan tree covered with thousands of branches
O king the great charioteers reached the banyan tree The best of the elephants saw that excellent tree
They got down from their chariots and released the brahmins from their horses O lord after taking bath in accordance with custom he spent the evening
Then the sun set on the best of the mountains Night fell on the mother of the entire world It is adorned with all the planets stars and constellations The sky looked as if it were cloudy It was worth seeing everywhere
Those beings who move about at night and those who move about by day are under the control of sleep
The noise of the creatures that roamed at night was terrible The flesh eaters were rejoicing and the dreadful night had arrived
At that dreadful night they were filled with sorrow and grief Kritavarma, Kripa and Draupadi sat down together.
They sat there mourning near the banyan tree That very purpose of the destruction of the Kurus and the Pandavas has been exceeded.
They sat down on the ground, their bodies covered with sleep. Struggling with exhaustion she was wounded by various arrows
Then the two great warriors of Kripabhoja fell asleep. They sat on the ground deserving of happiness and misery
O great king both of them were asleep exhausted and grieved Endowed with expensive beds they lay on the ground like orphans
The son of Drona, O Bharatha, was overcome with anger and rage. He did not fall asleep panting like a snake
Burning with anger he could not sleep The mightyarmed Ravana looked around the dreadful forest
Looking at the forest area inhabited by various creatures The mightyarmed Ravana beheld a herd of tigers inhabited by crows
There were thousands of crows that night. O son of the Kurus they sleep happily separately under separate shelters
While the crows were asleep they could be heard all around Suddenly he saw a dreadful looking owl passing by
The loud-voiced, huge-bodied Haryaksha, the yellow beaver. Its nails were very long and horrible and it moved swiftly like Garuda
Then he made a soft sound like an egg dissolving Then he prayed for a branch of the banyan tree, O Arjuna.
The bird approached the branch of the banyan tree The destroyer of crows killed many sleeping crows
He cut off the wings and heads of some of them The foot weapon also broke the feet of some of them In an instant the strong man killed those who stood in his sight
O lord with their limbs and bodies The whole circle of banyan trees was covered on all sides
Then Kausika the destroyer of enemies having killed the crows rejoiced
Having seen the action performed by Kausika during the night Determined to do so, Droni thought alone.
This bird has given me advice in the battle I think the time has come to destroy the enemies
It is not possible for me today to slay the Pandavas who have conquered Kashi. Strong, enthusiastic, achieving goals, hitters.
I promised to kill them from the king's presence He adopted a self-destructive behavior like the fire of a moth.
There is no doubt that one who is fighting justly will give up his life And by disguise there will be perfection and great destruction of enemies. There, from the doubtful, the meaning which becomes undoubted.
Many people and those who are experts in the scriptures believe in him Whatever may be said here is condemned and reviled by the world That is what a man should do while following the Kshatriya dharma. All these things were blasphemed and despised at every step They were made by the enemies of the Pandavas.
Those thinking of righteousness used to hear the Gita for this purpose Verses by those who observe justice, the meanings of the truth, and the seers of the truth.
When I was tired or torn or eaten by my enemies The enemy force should be attacked on departure or entry
He was asleep at midnight and lost his love. A different warrior and a force that is divided into two parts Thus he resolved to kill the sleeping men at night The son of Panchalaiona was mighty with the Pandavas.
He resolved again and again to think cruelly He woke up both his maternal uncle and Bhoja who were asleep
The two mighty highminded Kripabhojas woke up It is fitting that they should not reply to the question
He thought for a moment and said in a daze King Duryodhana, a single hero and mighty warrior, was slain. For whose sake we have no attachment to enmity with the Pandavas. He was purely valiant in battle alone with many hungry men The commander of the eleventh army was killed by Bhimasena
This is a cruel thing done by the mean Bhima. His head was crushed with his foot
The Panchalas roared and whispered and laughed. They blow hundreds of conches and beat drums in joy
The tumultuous sound of musical instruments mixed with the sounds of conches The dreadful wind blowing seemed to fill all directions
The horses were laughing and the elephants were galloping The loud roar of lions can be heard among the heroes
They were moving in the eastern direction with great joy The hair-raising sounds of chariots and wheels can be heard
The slaughter which the Pandavas committed against the sons of Dhritarashtra. The three of us are the only ones left in this great ordeal
Some of them had the life of a hundred serpents and others were skilled in all kinds of weapons Slain by the Pandavas, I think it is the end of time.
Surely this should be true of Karva Just as he is faithful to his difficult task even when it is accomplished
But they will be if wisdom is not removed from delusion. Tell us what is best for us in this great matter which is at stake
Vaishampayana said: That king, who had gone to heaven, was dwelling in the house of the gods. He was worshiped by the devatas sadhyas Maruts and Vasus
Traveling in the world of the gods and the world of Brahma, he is subdued by the pious. It is said that the king of the earth lived there for a long time
Once that Yayati the best of kings came to Indra. At the end of the story there Indra asked the lord of the earth.
Indra said: When that Purusha in your form, O king, took old age and walked about on the earth. Tell me the truth about what you said to him when you handed over the kingdom
Yayati said This whole subject is yours between the Ganges and the Yamuna. You are the king in the middle of the earth Your brothers are the ultimate rulers
and the patient is distinguished from the patient. The learned is superior to the non-human and also to the ignorant.
He who is rebuked should not cry, but should endure anger. He burns the screamer and finds good in him.
He should not be rude, nor should he be cruel, nor should he give the highest fear to the inferior. A woman living in this sinful world should not speak to anyone whose words frighten others
Aruntud, harsh, sharp-speaking, piercing men with thorns of speech. It should be known as the most auspicious, carrying the devil bound in the mouths of men.
He would be worshiped by the virtuous in front and protected by the virtuous from behind. He should tolerate the excessive arguments of the virtuous and follow the noble conduct of the virtuous.
The arrows of speech fall from his mouth and he grieves day and night when he is struck Those names of the other fall into the vital organs; a wise man should not create them in others.
For there is no such union in the three worlds. Compassion, friendship to all beings, charity and sweet speech.
Therefore, consolation should always be spoken and never harsh words. One should worship those who are worshipable, give and never beg.
Sanjaya said, O king, there are hundreds of thousands of infantry here and there. I shall tell thee, O Arjuna, about the unlimited battles fought.
No son was born to his father or father to his son Maurasa There was no brother to brother no sister to maternal uncle
Neither maternal uncle nor sister nor friend nor friend The Pandavas are fighting with the Kurus as if overwhelmed.
Some of the male tigers attacked the locals in their chariots. The ages were divided into ages, O best of the Bharatas.
These chariots and these chariots are the humps of the chariots. Some of them along with their associates were eager to kill each other
Some of them could not move and some of them stood in their chariots. The huge elephants fell down and were shattered by the elephants They tore each other in many ways with their horns in anger. O Lord elephants with gates and banners and excellent elephants O great king they advanced with swift huge elephants Struck by the teeth they cried out in great agony
They were acted out and beaten with the goad of hymns by the teachings Unbroken they went facing each other when they were broken
Some of the huge elephants were attached to them even when they were broken They roared like crows and fled in all directions
The serpents were properly carried and their faces were broken The best of elephants were pierced by slings hammers and arrows The marbles were shattered and they fell down dead Some of them ran in all directions roaring in fearful voices
The legs of the elephants were guarded by the armed chests of the strikers They wielded spears bows and immaculate axes clubs and spears and spears and spears. They also carried iron and paripas without swords and with pure sharp objects They were furious when they were caught and ran here and there O great king they appeared eager to kill each other
They rose without swords and were drenched in human blood The heroes appeared running towards each other
The heroic arms of the brides were thrown down A tumultuous sound arose as they fell to the very vital parts of the body
They were wounded with clubs and spears and pierced with sharp swords Their teeth were broken and crushed by their teeth Here and there crowds of men shouted at each other They heard the terrible words of the dead, O Arjuna.
Even horses ridden by horsemen wearing chamaras. They rushed at each other like swift swans
They were freed from the great ropes and adorned with golden rivers. They were swift and pure and sharp and resembled the arms of cows
Some jumped on horses at high speed to a great place. The heroes cut off the heads of the charioteers and horsemen
Many horsemen with spears bent at the ends. The charioteer reached the arrows and killed them
The elephants shone like nine clouds and threw their horses. The intoxicated men adorned with gold are crushing them with their feet
Elephants were also on the sides of the pots being broken Struck by the spears some of them cried out in great distress
The best of the elephants stirred up some of the horses and riders. At once they threw themselves into the crowd in a frightening manner
The elephants threw their horns at the horses and their riders Crushing the flocks of chariots they marched around with flags
Some of them were great elephants because of their masculinity and their intoxication They killed the horses and their riders with their hands and feet Horsemen and elephants and others in battle
They also placed elephants on the sides of the bodies of the statues They were swift and pure and sharp and resembled the arms of cows
They broke through the bodies of men and horses and the iron armor. The pure energies offered by the heroic arms fell down There are terrible images of meteors here and there, O lord. They were covered with island skins and covered with tiger skins They attacked the others in battle with their swords sharpened
He was flooded in anger and torn to pieces by one leg. They arrived showing off their birdskins and axes.
Some of them threw elephants and even chariots with their hands All directions were pulled together and all sounds were heard.
Some were pierced by cones and shattered by axes Some were cheered by the elephants while others were crushed by the horses They cut down the wheels of their chariots and cut them down with axes The men cried out, O king, and the relatives were bound here and there. Some sons others fathers others brothers with relatives maternal uncles sisters and others in battle
Many of them had their bowels scattered and their limbs broken, O Arjuna. Others were cut off their arms and torn in pieces by the Parthas.
Thirsty and eager to live they appeared screaming Some of them were overcome with thirst and were of little strength, O lord.
They fell to the ground in battle and searched for water They were drenched in floods of blood and tormented, O Bharatha. He severely blamed himself and your sons who were present
Other brave kshatriyas made enmity with each other They do not release their weapons nor do they cry out O mortal
They threatened each other here and there in delight In anger he bit the lid of the lake with his teeth They stare at each other with their faces crooked with their eyebrows Others were tormented by arrows and wounds The strong and mighty men rushed together without a whisper Other heroes also stood firm in the battle of another The chariots of prayers were crushed by the best of elephants O great king they looked like kimsuka trees with flowers
There were many terrible roars among the soldiers While the great dreadful Rama was destroying the best of heroes The father killed his son and the son killed his father in battle His sister and his maternal uncle and his sister and his maternal uncle
A friend and a friend and a relative and a relative. Thus fought there the Kurus with the Pandavas.
In the present and in that unlimited and terrible. The army of the Parthas trembled as they reached Bhishma.
Ketu, O best of the Bharatas, with the five-star rhythm. The mighty arms of the great charioteer were raised in silver. Then king Bhishma shone like the Moon by mount Meru
Dhritarashtra said: Tell me, O Sanjaya, the north and east sides of Meru. O highly intelligent one I have seen mount Malyavan in its entirety
Sanjaya said On the south side of the Nile and on the north side of mount Meru O King the northern Kurus are holy and are inhabited by siddhas
There are trees bearing honey and everlasting flowers and fruits The flowers are fragrant and the fruits are tasty
O lord of men there are some trees that bear the fruits of all desires O king there are other trees called milky trees
Those who always shed milk and six kinds of nectar Clothes and ornaments are produced in the fruits
All the jeweled ground is fine golden sand. O lord of men she is free from the touch of pleasure in all seasons
There are auspicious rivers with pleasant touch and delightful rivers All human beings who have fallen from the heavenly world are born there.
They were all of white descent and pleasing to look at Twins are born and women resemble apsaras
They drink the milk of those who are milky which is like nectar A twin is born in time and it grows equally.
He was endowed with equal beauty and virtues and also dressed in the same manner O lord I am attached to each one like a chakravaka
Those worlds are always healthy and cheerful Ten thousand years and ten hundred years. O great king they live and do not abandon each other They are very strong birds with sharp beaks called bharunda They carry away the dead bodies here and throw them into the caves The northern Kurus, O king, have been explained in brief.
I shall first tell you exactly what is on the side of mount Meru O lord of the world the coronation of his head was performed by Bhadrasva
There is a forest of bhadrasala and a huge tree called kalamara O great king the kalamara is an auspicious tree with everlasting flowers and fruits
Duma is also a yojana high and is inhabited by Siddhas and Charanas. There those men were white and bright and very strong.
The women were beautiful and pleasing in complexion like lilies They were as bright as the moon and had the color of the moon and their faces were like the full moon
They were experts in dancing and singing like the moon and the cold O best of the Bharatas he lived there for ten thousand years
They are ever young and drunk with the taste of kalamara on the south of the Nile and on the north of the Nishad.
There is a great eternal jambu tree named Sudarsana He is the fruit of all desires and is holy and is served by the Siddhas and Charanas.
The eternal island of Jambu is celebrated by his name A thousand and a hundred yojanas, O best of the Bharatas. The height of the king of trees resembles that of the lord of men A thousand and fifteen hundred gems The fruits of the tree are destroyed by the taste buds They make a loud noise as they fall
They release silvery taste into the king's body O lord of men the taste of her jambu fruits became a river
Having circumambulated mount Meru he proceeded to the northern Kurus There they were thirsty for peace of mind, O lord of men. When they drink the juice of that fruit old age does not afflict them There is a golden ornament called Jambunada That luminous one is born resembling the cowherd boys of Indra Humans are born there with the color of the young sun
Similarly on the peak of Malyavata there is always a fire for offering oblations The name of Samvartaka is Kalagni, O best of the Bharatas.
Similarly on the peak of Malyavata there is a river flowing eastwards Five or six thousand yojanas of garlands
There are born human beings of great silvery appearance All of them have fallen from the Brahmaloka and are all saintly in all respects.
They practice austerities and become intensely of high blood. They enter the Sun to protect all living beings
They were sixty thousand and sixty hundred. Surrounding the Sun they march in front of Aruna
Sixty thousand years and sixty hundred years. Scorched by the heat of the Sun they enter the orb of the Moon
Sauti said as soon as she was touched by the feet of the mighty Garuda He broke off a broken branch of a tree and held it alone
He worshiped her and looked at the great branch with a smile. Then he saw Valakhilya hanging there with their faces downcast ॥
The sages are hanging here I will not kill them Having observed the brahmarshis engaged in austerities
Then he thought that the branches falling on him would kill them The heroic Rama seized the elephant and the tortoise with his nails firmer
Terrified of its destruction the lord of the birds rushed forward Looking at them he seized the branches with his mouth
The great sages saw that his action was very fortunate O great bird their hearts trembled with wonder
This bird is carrying a heavy load Garuda is the best of birds and therefore he eats serpents
Then he slowly fell down shaking the mountains with his wings Thus the elephant and the tortoise flew to many places
For mercy he found no place for children's play He quickly reached Gandhamadana the best of mountains
There he saw Kasyapa his father engaged in austerities His father also beheld the bird of divine appearance
Endowed with splendour, energy and strength, the mind is fierce like the wind. It resembled a mountain and was raised like a brahmadanda
It is unthinkable, unthinkable, and terrifying to all beings. He possessed mighty prowess and was fierce He looked like fire
It is invincible and invincible to gods demons boars and demons It breaks the mountain peaks and dries up the waters of the sea
The stirring of the world is terrible and the sight of fate is equal. Then venerable Kasyapa observed him arriving Having understood his resolve she said
Kasyapa said My son do not dare you will not be in pain immediately Let not the enraged Valakhilyas and Marichipas burn you
Sauti said Then Kasyapa begged him for the sake of his son The fortunate Valakhilyas were purified of their sins by austerities
Kasyapa said: O ascetics, Garuda's undertaking for the welfare of the people. He intends to undertake a great feat You should give him permission
Sauti said Thus addressed by the Lord, the sages approached. Seeking austerities he left a branch of the holy Himavan mountain
Then when they had departed the son of Vinata met his father With his face turned to the branches he inquired of Kasyapa
"O lord where am I going to let go of this branch of the tree Please tell me about the place forbidden to humans
Then there was a deserted mountain and a cave covered with snow Kasyapa told him what was incomprehensible even to others
That great eagle pointed to the great abdomen of that mountain! Tarkshya with branches elephant and tortoise rushed at him with great speed
The bride did not want to marry that huge body with a hundred skins. The bird took hold of a huge branch of the tree and departed
He then came a hundred thousand yojanas away. Garuda the lord of birds will not be too late in time
At his father's words he went to the mountain in an instant There the flying creature released a huge branch with a loud noise
The king of the mountains trembled as his wings were blown away The melted trees showered flowers
The peaks of the mountain were shattered all around The huge mountain is adorned with gems and gold
Many of the branches were also struck by the branch. They shone with golden flowers like clouds at the end of lightning
They are golden-brown on the ground mixed with mountain minerals. The branches illuminated by the rays of the Sun shone brightly
Then the best of birds climbed the peak of that mountain. Garuda devoured both the elephant and the tortoise
After devouring both the tortoise and the elephant Then he jumped down from the peak of the mountain with great speed
Then the gods proceeded to announce calamities and fears Then Indra's beloved thunderbolt blazed out of fear
Flames fell from the sky with smoke Similarly among the Vasus Rudras and Aditi in all respects and also of the Sadhyas and Maruts and all other hosts of gods. They attacked each other with their respective weapons
Then in an unprecedented battle between gods and demons Thousands of meteors fell with thunderous winds
The sky was clear and there was a loud noise. The lord of the gods also showered blood
They dimmed the garlands of the gods and took away their splendour. Terrible clouds of upheaval rained down abundant blood
They rubbed the dust on the crowns of others Then the hundred seasons with the gods were terrified. Seeing the terrible calamities he said to Brihaspati
Indra said: Why, O venerable one, have these calamities suddenly arisen? I do not see an enemy who would attack us in battle
Brihaspati said O lord of the gods it is because of your offense and negligence that Satakrata By the austerities of the great sages Balakhilya
He was the son of sage Kasyapa and the astronaut of Vinata The mighty Ravana assuming any form at will assumed the form of the moon
The best of the strong birds is capable of stealing the moon. Everything is possible in this, and even the impossible should be accomplished.
Sauti said On hearing these words Indra the keeper of nectar replied A bird of great prowess is ready to snatch the moon
I am addressing you that this is not by the power of Hari His strength is incomparable Brihaspati said
The gods were astonished to hear his words and made an effort Vajra and mighty Indra surrounded the nectar
They were wearing colorful golden jewelery. They wore expensive shields decorated with vaidurya
The skins on the limbs are also shiny and firm. Various kinds of weapons of dreadful forms were also deployed
The best of the gods raised their cold sharp edges. There were sparks and flames and smoke everywhere
wheels spears tridents and axes. The shaktis were of various sharpness and the hands were pure They displayed fierce clubs in the form of their bodies
They were adorned with divine ornaments with their radiant weapons Hosts of gods spotless with the sun stood there
Incomparable strength and courage, Jeso, with a steadfast mind, protects the immortal. The gods who tore the cities of the asuras shone with their bodies burning like flames
Thus the gods stood in the best of battle crowded with hundreds of thousands of iron clubs. The heat of the sky shone like a melted sky
Vaishampayana said: Dhritarashtra, the king of men, having understood the opinion of his son. Considering this fate to be difficult the king acted
Vidura, the best of learned men, was unjustly addressed in that way. He did not rejoice at the words of his brother and replied
Vidura said: O king I am not pleased Do not do this to Praisha I am afraid of the destruction of my family O king I suspect this is for gambling
Dhritarashtra said: O wounded one, quarrel will not torment me here, unless fate is reversed. The thread, however, is under the control of the destined, and this whole world moves not independently.
Narada said: I shall now describe the assembly in the south, O Yudhisthira. Listen to it. That which Visvakarma performed for Vaivasvata, O Arjuna.
That assembly of Taijasi, O king, was a hundred yojanas in length. Even though it is not endowed with breadth and width, O Arjuna, it is greater. She shines like the sun and assumes the form of desire everywhere She was neither too cold nor too hot and delighted the mind
There is no sorrow, no old age, no hunger, no thirst, no unpleasantness in her. Neither misery nor fatigue nor adversity nor even.
All desires, both divine and human, abide in her. O subduer of enemies food is abundant in taste It is licked and chewed and the drink is hearty tasty and delightful His garlands always smelled like lotuses and produced the fruits of desire
The waters are juicy and cold and hot. There were holy royal sages and spotless brahmarshis in that city
O dear child they worship Yama Vaivasvata with delight Yayati, Nahusha, Puru, Mandhata, Somaka and Nriga.
The royal sages who had accomplished their prowess and whose reputation had been heard were frightened Arishtanemi, Siddha, Kritavega and Nimi. Pratardana, Shibirmatsya, Pruthulaksha and Brihadratha. Varta, Marutta, Kusika, Sankasya and Sankritivava. Chaturashvah Sadashvormi: and Kartavirya, the earthling. Bharata Suratha Sunitha and Nishaddha Nala Divodasa, Sumana, Ambarisha and Bhagiratha. The horse is a good horse, a horse to be killed, a horse of great speed, and a horse of great ears. The bull horse Vasumana and Kshupa are very strong Rushadur Vrishasena and Purukutsa the flag bearer and charioteer Artisena and Dilipa and the great Ushinara. Aushinari, Pundarika, Sharyati, Sarabha and Shuchi. Ango, Arishta, Vena, Dushyanta, Srinjaya and Jaya. Bhangasuri Sunitha Nishadha and Vahinara Karandham, Bahnik, Sudyumna, and the strong Madhu. Similarly Aila and Marutta the mighty lord of the earth Pigeon-haired Grass and Sahadeva and Arjuna. The king Vyasva, Sasva, Krishasva and Shashabindu. King Dasaratha and Kakutstha and Pravardhana Alarka Kakshasena Gaya and Gaurasva The sons of Jamadagni Rama Nabhaga and Sagara Bhuridyumna, Mahasva, Prithasva and Janaka. King Vainya, Varisena, Purujit and Janamejaya. Brahmadatta and Trigarta were attendants of the king Indradyumna, the terrible kneeler, the back of the sinless rhythm. Then came Padma Muchukanda Bhuridyumna and Prasenajit Arishtanemi, Sudyumna, Prithulasva and Ashtaka. One hundred fishes one hundred kings one hundred neepas one hundred cows
Dhritarashtra and Janamejaya, one hundred and eighty. One hundred heroic enemies were given to him by Brahma
Two hundred Bhishmas are also here, and so is a hundred Bhimas. There were one hundred serpents and one hundred horses among the Vindhyas
One hundred of the palashas are to be understood as one hundred of the kashakushas and others. O best of kings also your father is Shantanu and Pandu
Ushangava, Shataratha, Jayadratha, king of the gods. The wise royal sage Vrishadarbha accompanied by his ministers
Then there are thousands of other rabbit drops that have passed away He performed many great horse sacrifices and offered generous gifts
These royal sages are pious, renowned and well-versed. O best of kings in that assembly they worship Vaivasvata
Agastya, Matanga, Kala and also Death. And also the performers of sacrifices, and also the Siddhas, and those embodied in Yoga. The fathers who drank foam and heat from the fire There were also others who were offering sacrificial offerings in their own forms
And the cycle of time is directly the venerable Havyavahana. Men of evil deeds die in the southern solstice
And those who are in the eyes of time and the men of Yama. There are shimshapapalasha and kashakusha and other trees in that river O lord of men incarnate they worship the king of righteousness These and many others are members of the assembly of the patriarchs They cannot be enumerated by names or by actions
For that assembly, O Arjuna, is unconstrained, and it is a beautiful assembly of desires. It was created by Visvakarma after performing austerities for a long time
Burning and shining with her own effulgence, O Bharatha. Those who are virtuous in vows and truthful go to that place by performing severe austerities They are peaceful, renounced, pure, and purified by pious action. They all had resplendent bodies and spotless clothes
They all wore garlands of colorful ornaments and burnt earrings They were adorned with meritorious deeds
There were great gandharvas and hosts of apsaras Musical instruments dance songs laughter and laughter in every way
There are holy smells and sounds in her all around, O Arjuna. Divine garlands are also offered daily
One hundred hundred thousand righteous men worshiped him The highminded women endowed with beauty worship the great soul
O king such was the assembly of the great king of his fathers I shall tell you about the assembly of Varuna garlanded with lotuses
Arjuna said Those who sacrifice with faith, abandoning the precepts of the scriptures. But what is their fixation, O Krishna, is Sattva, Rajas or Tamas?
The Supreme Personality of Godhead said: There are three kinds of faith in the embodied, that which is inherent in nature. Hear now the consciousness of the Sattvic, Rajasic and Tamasic.
Everyone's faith is in accordance with Sattva, O Bharatha. This man is full of faith; whatever faith he has, that is that.
The Sattvic worship the gods, the Yakshas and the Rakshasas, the Rajasic. Others, men of the Tamasic nature, worship the dead and hosts of beings.
Those who practice terrible austerities prescribed by the unscriptural. Possessed of pride and egoism, endowed with the strength of lust and passion.
Slimming the unconscious host of ghosts in the body. And also Me within the body, know thou to be those of demoniac determination.
Food is also dear to everyone in three ways. Sacrifice, austerity and charity; hear now the distinction between them.
They increase life, strength, health, happiness and pleasure. Foods that are juicy, greasy, stable and hearty are dear to the Sattvic.
They are bitter, salty, very hot, sharp, dry and burning. Foods desired by the Rajasic cause pain, grief and disease.
That which is gone, gone, pus, and parched. Even leftover food is impure and dear to the Tamasic.
The sacrifice which is offered by the unfruitful eyes as seen by the law. That Sattvic man, having fixed his mind that sacrifice must be performed.
But that which is for the sake of pride and for the sake of fruition. That sacrifice which is worshipped, O best of the Bharatas, know thou to be Rajasic.
Food without rituals, food not created, gifts without mantras. They declare a sacrifice devoid of faith to be Tamasic.
Worship of gods, brahmins, teachers and wise men, purity and simplicity. Celibacy and non-violence are called bodily austerities.
That which is true and pleasant and good is spoken without anxiety The study of the Vedas and also the practice of the Vedas are called austerities.
Peace of mind, gentleness, silence, self-control. Purification of the mind is called this austerity of the mind.
That austerity performed by men with supreme faith is of three kinds. Those endowed with the eyes of the sun without fruit declare it to be Sattvic.
That which is done with austerity and pride for the sake of honor, respect and worship. That which is done is said here to be Rajasic, movable and immovable.
That austerity which is performed by tormenting the self by foolish grasp. Or for the destruction of another, that is declared to be Tamasic.
That which is given to the unfortunate is a gift that is to be given. That charity given in a place and time and to a person is regarded as Sattvic.
That which is done for the sake of reward or for the sake of reward And if it is given with great difficulty, that charity is regarded as Rajasic.
That which is given at an untimely place and to those who are not worthy. That which is honored by the hearers and despised is declared to be Tamasic.
The instruction of the Brahman, Om Tatsad, is said to be of three kinds. In the past he ordained the Brahmanas the Vedas and sacrifices
Therefore, by saying, Domi, sacrifice, charity and austerity are the actions. They are always carried out in accordance with the prescribed rituals of the Brahma-vadis.
The acts of sacrifice and austerity are the fruits without contemplating that. And various acts of charity are performed by those with eyes of liberation.
This is used in the sense of goodness and in the sense of goodness. Thus, O Arjuna, the word sattva is applied to praiseworthy action.
The state in sacrifice, austerity and charity is also called Sad. And also action for that purpose is called Sat.
That which is offered, given, performed austerities and performed without faith. It is said to be non-existent, O Arjuna, and that is not here for us after death.
Bhishma said This four-armed Triaksha, born in the royal family of Chedi. He roared and roared like the weight of a roar
His parents and relatives were frightened Seeing his disfigurement both of them decided to give him up
Then he accompanied the king his wife his ministers and priests Her heart bewildered with anxiety she uttered disembodied words
This is your king's son born prosperous and strong Therefore do not be afraid of us O inexhaustible one protect this child
Neither death nor time has come for him O lord of men that destroyer of death was born with the weapon
Then the words uttered by the promise became hidden. Overwhelmed with affection for her son the mother said
Whoever spoke these words to my son I offer my obeisances to him with folded palms Let him speak these words again In fact, if the Lord is a god or any other. I wish to hear who will die for my son
Then he spoke these words again to the ghost who had entered. Both his arms were more than the size of the one held on his lap They will fall to the ground like five-headed snakes. This is the third eye on the forehead of the child Whoever he sees will drown will be his death Hearing the three-eyed four-armed Lord thus described.
All the kings of the earth came to see him The king (Dasaratha) paid due respects to those who had arrived
Then she placed her son on the lap of each king In this way thousands of kings were separated in order Climbing on the lap of the baby he did not find that proof Having heard this the two mighty warriors stayed in Dwaravati
Then Sankarshana and Janardana reached Chedipura. Then Yadava went to see his father's sister
Having saluted her and the king in accordance with custom and excellence Rama and Kesava sat down inquiring about their welfare
Then he paid homage to the two heroes with even greater affection The goddess herself placed her son on the lap of Damodara
As soon as he placed his arms on his lap They fell down and his eyes sank into the forehead
Seeing this Jasta was distressed and asked Krishna for a boon O Krishna, O mightyarmed one, grant me a boon for I am afflicted with fear.
You are the comfort of news and the giver of fearlessness to those who are afraid Thus addressed Krishna the delight of the Yadus replied
O goddess knower of righteousness have no fear You have nothing to fear from me What boon shall I bestow on my cousin
Whether it is possible or not I will do as you say. Thus addressed she addressed Krishna the delight of the Yadus
O tiger among the Yadus O mighty one for my sake forgive the offenses of Sisupala Know this to be my boon O lord
Sri Krishna said: I have forgiven this cousin for a hundred offenses. Do not indulge in grief for your son who deserves to be killed
Bhishma said Thus is this sinful king Shishupala of very slow intelligence. O valiant one proud of the boons of Govinda he is summoning you
Vaishampayana said Then all those Kauravas and Pandavas except Bhima. They set out for Gajasahvaya engaged in sports and pastimes
They were accompanied by stable elephants and many other wonderful animals While we were speaking Bhimasena went ahead of us Then the sinful Duryodhana saw Bhima there. Along with his brothers he entered the cheerful city
But righteous Yudhisthira did not know the sin in himself. By his own inference he perceives the Supreme Sadha.
Then Partha, affectionate to his brother, approached his mother. Bhima saluted Kunti and said O mother Bhima has come here
O auspicious one where has he gone I cannot see him here We searched all over the gardens and forests That is why they did not see that heroic Bhima Thinking that he had already left us all of us
We have arrived, O most fortunate one, with a troubled inner self. Where did he go when he arrived here? Where did you send him?
O illustrious lady tell me about the mightyarmed Bhimasena O beautiful lady my feelings towards that hero are not purified
Because I thought Bhima was asleep he was killed Thus addressed by the wise king of righteousness Kunti "Alas, alas," she replied to Yudhisthira in confusion. My son I do not see Bhima nor does he approach me
Try to find him quickly with his younger brothers. Having said this to her eldest son she was distressed at heart Then Kunti brought the Kshatriyas and spoke these words. O venerable kshatriyas where has Bhimasena gone? He is not visible
All the brothers and sisters came out of the garden There is only one strongarmed frightening one who does not approach me here
Nor does he always please the eye of Duryodhana. He is cruel wicked mean greedy for kingdom and shameless
Even if he killed that hero Suyodhana became furious My mind is agitated and my heart is burning
Vidura said Do not say so O auspicious one take care of the rest On being ordered back the evilminded one will attack you even in the rest of the world
May your daughter live a long life just as the great sage said Your son will come and instill pleasure in you You
Vaishampayana said Having thus spoken, the learned Vidura went to his abode. Worried Kunti sat at home with her sons
Then on the eighth day the Pandavas awoke. Then the mighty Rama of immeasurable strength was in the worn out juice
The serpents saw the Pandavas awakening. The demons were anxious to console him with these words
That which you have drunk, O mightyarmed one, is this juice full of energy. Therefore you will be unbearable in battle with the strength of tens of thousands of elephants
Go home today and bathe yourself in the divine rituals O chief of the Kurus your brothers are grieving without you
