Look at the strength of my arms and my superhuman prowess O descendant of Bhrigu whatever I can do even after my departure
O brahmin I shall do that I shall fight with you at Kurukshetra O effulgent Rama prepare for the duel as I wish
O Rama I killed you there tormented by a hundred arrows Purified with weapons you will attain the worlds conquered in the great battle
O dear warrior go and return to Kurukshetra O mightyarmed one I shall come there to fight you O fodder
O Rama did you perform the purification of your father there in the past There, O Bhrigu, I too shall perform purification by killing you.
"O Rama come there quickly I shall destroy this ancient city for your sake Tell the brahmins Ram often
And whatever you talk about in the year. I alone have conquered the kshatriyas in this world Listen
Neither Bhishma nor a Kshatriya like me was born then. You have kindled the effulgence born in the grass
He who will destroy your warlike milk and desire. That I was born, O mighty-armed Bhishma, the conqueror of the cities of the enemy. O Rama I shall undoubtedly dispel your pride in the battle
Bhishma said Then Rama, as if laughing, addressed me, O Bharatha. Fortunately, O saintly Bhishma, thou wishest to fight with me in battle.
O son of the Kurus I am going to Kurukshetra with you O scorcher of enemies I shall carry out your words Come there
There I killed you mother with a hundred arrows O Bhishma let the river Jahnavi behold the devourer of vultures and herons
I am served by Siddhas and Charanas looking at you miserable O king let the queen cry today when I have killed her
Half the most fortunate daughter of Bhagiratha deserves this. She gave birth to you slow and afflicted with lust for war
Come, go with me, Bhishma, mad for war. O Arjuna O best of the Bharatas accept everything including the chariot
While I was speaking to Rama the conqueror of enemy cities I bowed my head to Rama and said 'Let it be so'
Having said this Rama set out for Kurukshetra desiring to fight I entered the city and informed Satyavati
Then he was blessed and greeted by his mother. "O effulgent one saying to the brahmins 'I wish you good luck'
He mounted a beautiful silver chariot on white horses The soup pot was its own place and the tigers were surrounded by them
It was armed with great weapons and equipped with all kinds of equipment He was a hero of that noble race and wellversed in the art of horses
That which is done by a learned charioteer who has seen his actions many times I was bitten by a white shield with a body
O best of Bharatas he almost took up his white bow He was wearing a white umbrella on his head
O lord of men he was also beaten with white fans He wore white robes and a white turban and wore all white ornaments
Praised by Jayashi, he came out of the elephant's den. O best of the Bharatas Kurukshetra is the battlefield
The horses were driven by the charioteer in the great battle O king the wind of my mind was carrying me away severely
I went to that Kurukshetra and that mighty Rama O king they suddenly attacked each other for battle
Then I stayed to see Rama who was very ascetic Then he took hold of the best of the conchshells, the first and the best.
O king there were brahmins ascetics and forest dwellers Then the gods and hosts of Indra beheld the divine battle
Then divine garlands appeared here and there There were divine musical instruments and clusters of clouds
Then all those ascetics followed Bhrigu. The spectators gathered around the battlefield
Then the goddess who desires the welfare of all beings said to me O king your mother is in her own right What is your intention
O chief of the Kurus I shall go and beg Jamadagni Again and again he said 'Do not fight with Bhishma's disciple'
O son of the earth do not restrain a brahmin in this way It was said that he was fighting in battle with Jamadagni
Isn't the killer of a kshatriya as mighty as Hare? I know that Rama is your son and you wish to fight him
Then I bowed to the goddess with folded hands and said O best of the Bharatas everything happened as it happened at the Swayamvara
And as I urged Rama in the past, O king of kings. The ancient rituals performed by the daughter of the king of Kasi
Then my mother Mahanadi approached Rama The sage Bhrigu looked at him for his envy and forgave him
Do not fight with Bhishma, said the disciple. And he said to her, Turn away Bhishma alone, who was begging. I approached him saying 'He does not fulfill my desire'
Vaishampayana said Then Ganga, out of affection for her son, returned to Bhishma. His eyes agitated with anger he did not utter a word to her
Then the righteous Bhrigu the best of great ascetics appeared Then the best of brahmins summoned him for battle
Markandeya said: The planets and their sub-planets, the sages and the mothers. The hosts of the council were proud with their faces like fire These and many other dreadful inhabitants of heaven Surrounded by the great army she stood with hosts of mothers Seeing his doubtful victory the lord of the gods desired victory Along with the gods he rode on the shoulder of Airavata
The mighty Ravana took Vala and was surrounded by all the hosts of gods Desiring to destroy the great army Indra advanced at once The army of the gods roared fiercely and roared with great splendor He was armed with wonderful flags and carried various vehicles and bows He was dressed in fine clothes and decorated with splendour. The young prince followed Indra as he approached to kill him Roaring, O Arjuna, the mighty Lord of the gods goes swiftly. Delighting the army of gods they desired to kill the son of fire He was worshiped by the gods and also by the great sages. Then Indra approached Kartikeya
Then lord of the gods along with the gods roared like a lion On hearing the sound Guha roared like the ocean
Its loud sound shone like the ocean The army of gods wandered about unconscious here and there
The fireman saw the gods approaching to kill him. Furious he emitted flames of fire from his mouth
It burned the armies of the gods trembling on the ground They had burning heads and bodies and carried blazing weapons They suddenly appeared like busy clusters of stars Burning with fire they sought refuge in the son of fire Then the gods left Valadhar and attained peace Abandoned by the gods Indra dropped Vala on Skanda
He quickly struck the right side of Skanda when it was released O great king it pierced the side of that great soul
Another man was born to Skanda from the blow of Vala He was young armed with gold and possessed of power and wore divine earrings
Vishakha was born from the womb of Vala Seeing his lips born shining like the fire of time Out of fear Indra took refuge in him with folded hands Skanda, the best of the army, gave him safety. Then the delighted gods played musical instruments and saluted him
Uma said: O lord Bhaganetra, O Pushno, fall of your teeth. O Triaksha destroyer of Daksha's sacrifice this is my great doubt
The fourfold nature was created by the Supreme Personality of Godhead in the past by Svayambhuva. By what consequence of action does a vaisya attain to the status of a Sudra?
By what means can a Vaishya or a Kshatriya become a Brahmin or a Kshatriya? O lord how can righteousness be reversed
Or by what action is a Brahmin born in the womb of a Sudra? By what action, O lord, does a Kshatriya attain to the status of a Sudra?
O sinless lord of ghosts this is my doubt How can the three castes by nature attain to Brahmanhood in this world?
Sri Maheshwara said: Brahminhood, O goddess, is difficult to attain, and by nature, O auspicious one, a Brahmin. I think that a kshatriya or a vaisya or a sudra is by nature
A brahmin is deprived of his place by his evil deeds Having obtained the eldest caste a brahmin should therefore protect him
Standing by the Brahmin dharma, he lives by the Brahminhood. Whether he is a Kshatriya or a Vaisya he attains to the state of Brahman.
But he who renounces his brahminhood and practices the Kshatriya Dharma. He who is deviated from the Brahminhood is born in the womb of a Kshatriya.
And a brahmin who takes refuge in greed and delusion and performs vaisya rituals. Having attained brahminhood which is rare he always acts with little intelligence That Brahmin attains the status of a Vaishya or a Vaishya attains the status of a Sudra. A brahmin who has fallen from his own duty thereafter attains to the status of a Sudra.
There he went to hell and was expelled from the caste A Sudra who has been deprived of the world of Brahma is born.
O most fortunate one a kshatriya or a vaisya or a righteous woman He abandons his own duties and engages in the duties of a Sudra. He was deviated from his place and became a hybrid of castes A Brahmin, a Kshatriya, a Vaisya, such a man attains to the status of a Sudra.
But he who is a Buddha by his own Dharma, knowledge or realization, is impure. He who knows righteousness and is devoted to righteousness enjoys the fruits of righteousness
"O Devi this is also another statement declared by Brahma The sacrificial Adhyatma is served by the virtuous for the sake of righteousness.
"O goddess the food of the hosts is fierce and condemned Evil food should never be eaten, nor should food of a Sudra be ever eaten.
O Devi food of a sudra is always condemned by the great gods I think this is the proof emanating from the mouth of my grandfather
A brahmin who dies in her stomach with the remains of a sudra's food He who performs the sacrifice by offering sacrificial fire shall attain the state of a Sudra.
He was removed from the Brahma-sthana by the rest of the Sudras. A Brahmin becomes a Sudra There is no need to think about it
A brahmin who dies with the remains of food in his stomach A brāhmaṇa should enter that womb on which he lives
He who despises the rare attainment of auspiciousness as a Brahmin. He who eats food that is not fit to eat will fall down from being a brahmin
He is a drunkard a brahmachari a petty thief and unclean when he is broken He is devoid of study he is sinful greedy immoral and deceitful Avrati, a husband of a bull, a pot-eater, and a seller of moon. A brahmin who is devoid of service falls down from the womb of Brahma
He who sleeps with his teacher, betrays his teacher and is fond of cursing his teacher. Even the knower of Brahman falls down, a Brahmin born of Brahman.
"O Devi by these auspicious deeds performed A Sudra attains to the status of a Brahmin and a Vaisya attains to the status of a Kshatriya.
All the duties of the Sudras are done according to the law and the ordinance. Render service and attendance to the eldest caste with diligence
A Sudra who is always on the right path should do so without hesitation. He showed hospitality to gods and brahmins and observed vows
He used to go to the seasons and eat regularly He was intelligent He looked for invisible people He did not eat the rest of the food
A Sudra who does not eat meat in vain attains Vaishya status. He speaks the truth, speaks egotism, is free from duality and is well versed in peace.
He performs daily sacrifices and is pure, devoted to his study. He was self-controlled and honored brahmins and adorned all castes He observed a household vow and ate two meals a day. He ate the rest of the food and had conquered his food He was free from desire and devoid of egoism They worshiped the fire sacrifice and offered sacrifices in accordance with the ordinance. Having not eaten the rest of the food he received all the guests A Brahmin who is prescribed by the Tretagni Mantra becomes a Vaishya. That Vaisya is born in a highly pure family of a Kshatriya.
That Vaishya was born a Kshatriya and was cultured from birth. A brahmin who is observant of vows is brought in and honored
He gives, performs sacrifices, and receives rich gifts. Having studied, seeking heaven, he always took refuge in the fire of Treta.
He always gave hands to the needy and ruled the people with righteousness Truthful He who sees happiness always acts truthfully
The punishment of righteousness is not impunity but the discipline of righteousness It is controlled by the instruments of work and is characterized by six parts
Those who are conversant with economics do not voluntarily serve in the rural religion A righteous man should always lie down with his wife during the menstrual period
He was always fasting, disciplined, engaged in his study, and pure. He always lay down in the fire house in the midst of the peacocks
Sumana always extended hospitality to all the three classes Saying that it is always perfect for Sudras who desire food.
Whether it is from the meaning or from desire, one should not notice anything. He who performs rituals for the sake of ancestors gods and guests
He worships in his own house according to law and also eats food He offered oblations in the fire sacrifice three times in accordance with tradition
He was killed in battle for the welfare of cows and brahmins Having purified himself by chanting the mantras of Tretagni he becomes a brahmin
Endowed with knowledge and science, he is Sanskrit and well versed in the Vedas. A righteous brahmin becomes a kshatriya by his own actions
By these fruits of action, O goddess, Uddhava of a low caste family. Even a Sudra endowed with the Agama becomes a Sanskritized Brahmin.
A Brahmin is also uncircumcised and eats all kinds of food. He who renounces Brahminhood becomes such a Sudra.
By pure actions, O Devi, a pure soul and conquered senses. Brahma himself said that even a Sudra should be served like a Brahmin
Nature and action are auspicious where even a Sudra remains. I think he should be understood as distinguished among the brahmins
There is no ritual in the womb, no hearing, no progeny. The reasons for becoming a brahmin are the circumstances themselves
All this is prescribed by the circumstances of the Brahmins in this world. But even a Sudra, established in the profession, attains to the status of a Brahmin.
O beautiful hips my nature is brahmin and my mind is equal everywhere Wherever Brahman, transcendental and pure, dwells, that is the Brahmin.
These vaginal fruits, O goddess, indicate the part of the place. Brahma himself, the bestower of boons, who created the creatures, said this.
Even a Brahmin walks a great field in the world like a foot. Whatever seeds are sown there is agriculture in the future after death
He should always be a victim of obstacles and a follower of the right path. One who desires to live should follow the path of Brahman
A householder who studies the code should be at home. And it should always be done by one who studies himself and by one who lives by study.
For a brahmin who is thus established is on the right path and stands on the right path. He who meditates on the kindled fire is fit for becoming Brahman.
O goddess one should attain brahminhood and protect it with self-control O lady with a pure smile by accepting the vagina and giving and performing rituals
I have told you this secret so that a Sudra may become a Brahmin. Or a Brahmin who has fallen from righteousness as he attains to the status of a Sudra.
I have told you this secret so that a Sudra may become a Brahmin. Or a Brahmin who has fallen from righteousness as he attains to the status of a Sudra.
Sanjaya said: That great-minded man is greatly enlightened by the eloquence of your son. Overcome with great grief he did not utter even a single unpleasant word
He meditated for a long time and was filled with sorrow and anger. Like a breathing serpent he threw us down with his whistle
He lifted his eyes as if burning with anger, O Bharatha. He is the best among the knowers of the worlds of gods asuras and gandharvas
He spoke these words to your son before the Sama. Why, O Duryodhana, dost thou thus deprive me of thy words?
You love what is happening and what you can do. I sacrificed my life in battle for your pleasure
But when the brave Pandavas satisfied the fire in Khandava. Having defeated Indra in battle is enough proof of that
And when you, O mightyarmed one, were killed by the gandharvas with their might. The son of Pandu released enough proof of that.
O lord it is enough evidence that your heroic brothers and the charioteer's son Radha are fleeing
And that we were all together in Viratanagar then. The fact that he alone was prepared is sufficient proof of that
And Drona, who was furious in battle, and defeated me in battle. He gave him enough clothes to prove his identity
Similarly, Draupadi, the great archer, and also Saradvata. Having conquered the cow planet in the past is enough proof of that
And when he conquered Karna, who always thought himself a man. He gave adequate clothes to Uttara as proof of his prowess
The wind shields were invincible even to Vasava in battle. Arjuna, having won the battle, is sufficient proof of that.
Who can then defeat the fierce Pandavas in battle? He whose protector is the protector of the universe holds a conch disc and club
Vasudeva is the infinite power and the cause of creation and destruction. Lord of all, God of gods, Supreme Soul, eternal.
O king you have been addressed many times by great sages like Narada But out of delusion thou knowest not what to say, O Suyodhana.
For a man who wishes to die looks at all the golden trees. Similarly, in Gandhara, you see the opposite.
He himself made great enmity with the Pandavas and Sanjaya. Fight them and we shall see them in battle Be a man.
I, however, gathered all the Somakas and Panchalas. O tiger among men I shall kill you except Shikhandi
"Or killed by them in battle I shall go to the abode of Yama "Or by killing them in battle I shall give you pleasure
In the past a woman named Shikhandi was born in the royal palace By the boon given to him a male was born and that woman is called Shikhandini
I will not kill him even at the cost of my life, O Bharatha! That woman who was created by the mother is Shikhandi.
Sleep happily in Gandhara and tomorrow the doer of the great battle. People will tell about him as long as the earth remains
Thus addressed your son went out, O lord of the people. Having bowed his head to his preceptor Rama returned to his abode
Then the king arrived and dismissed the great crowd Then the destroyer of enemies entered the destruction at once
The king entered the city and spent the night there The king got up early in the morning and addressed them
Command the king to mobilize his army Alas today Bhishma will slay the Somakas in anger in battle
Hearing this Duryodhana wept bitterly at night O king he thought that it was as if he had given his own command
Let him go to the supreme state of indifference and condemn the subjugation of others. Shantanava, desiring to fight, meditated for a long time on Arjuna in battle.
Ingitte, however, knew it and thought about it. O great king Duryodhana urged Duryodhana
Let the chariots of Durshasana and the guards of Bhishma be engaged at once. Mobilize all twenty-two armies
I have been thinking about this for years Slaughter of the Pandavas and their armies and attainment of the kingdom
I think the best thing to do there is to protect Bhishma himself. He will protect us and help us from the forest and the Parthas in the battle.
The pure soul said I shall not kill Shikhandi That king is preceded by a woman therefore I am young in battle
The world knows that I am doing it to please my father. O mightyarmed one in the past he gave up his prosperous kingdom and his wives Heard.
I have never accepted a woman like this nor have I ever seen a woman before O best among men I tell you the truth I shall kill you in battle
O king if this Sikhandi was born of a woman as described in your endeavor then Sikhandi was born
He became a virgin and became a man and he will fight me. I shall by no means shoot my arrows in front of him
For in battle, O dear, the Kshatriyas are the conquerors of the Pandavas. I shall kill all the others who have reached the battlefield
Thus, O best of Bharatas, Ganga, the knower of the scriptures, spoke to me. I think that I should protect Ganga with all my heart
A wolf will kill a lion in a great battle if it is not protected Let us not kill Ganga with Shikhandi like a wolf
His maternal uncle Shakuni, Shalya, Kripa and Drona were twenty-two. That which they protect, O Ganga, in that protected place, sure victory. .
On hearing these words of Duryodhana They surrounded the Ganges with their chariots from all sides
And your sons, O Ganga, surrounded you and went away happily. Shaking the earth and the heavens, and shaking the Pandavas.
They were great charioteers with wellequipped chariots and teeth They surrounded Bhishma in the battle and stood still, bitten.
Just as the gods and demons in battle with the thunderbolt. All of them stood guarding that great charioteer
Then King Duryodhana again addressed Ghatara. The left wheel is Yudhanu and Uttamauja is the right wheel. These are the protectors of Arjuna, and Arjuna is also a Shikhandi. He was protected by Arjuna and thus deprived of us. Do so that Bhishma may not kill us, O evil ruler. Your son Durshasana heard the words of his brother
With Bhishma at the head he set out with the army. Seeing Bhishma surrounded by a herd of chariots.
Arjuna, the best of charioteers, said to Dhrishtadyumna. Shikhandi, the tiger of men, was led by Bhishma, O King. O Panchalya place him today and I shall be his protector'
Uma said: O Lord of all beings, worshiped by the gods and demons. O lord tell me undoubtedly what is right and what is wrong for men
For man is always of three kinds by action, mind and speech. He is bound by the ropes of bonds or released again
By what character or conduct or what kind of action By what news or virtues do men go to heaven here?
Sri Maheshwara said: O Devi, knower of the truth of Dharma and Artha, eternal in Dharma and engaged in restraint. Listen to this question which is for the benefit of all living beings and enhances intelligence
They are devoted to truth and righteousness and are devoid of all genders. Those men who enjoy the wealth obtained by righteousness go to heaven
They are bound neither by iniquity nor by righteousness, their doubts cut off. They know the truth of the origin of annihilation, they know everything, they see everything. Men devoid of passion are liberated from the bonds of action.
Those who do not harm anything by action, mind or speech. By which they are attached to something they are not bound by actions.
They were virtuous and compassionate and refrained from risking their lives The self-controlled, who are equally hateful and dear, are freed from the bonds of action.
They are compassionate to all beings and faithful to all living beings. Those men who have abandoned the news of violence will go to heaven.
They were always free from affection for others and avoided others' wives Those men who eat food obtained by righteousness go to heaven
Those who always treated him like a brother sister and daughter Those men who live with other men's wives go to heaven
They retired from the army and were always satisfied with their wealth Those men who live on their own fortunes go to heaven.
Those who are devoted to their wives and who follow the seasons Those men who enjoy the pleasures of the countryside go to heaven.
Those whose eyes are always veiled by the character of other men's wives Men who have conquered the senses and are devoted to virtue go to heaven.
This path created by the gods should always be followed by men The path made by Akhaya should always be followed by the wise
Endowed with charity, righteousness and austerity, character, purity and compassion. He should always be served by men for the sake of occupation or for the sake of righteousness Those who desire to live in heaven should not serve your latter
Uma said: But by the word he is bound, by which he is freed or again. O sinless Lord of all beings, O God, tell me those actions of mine.
Sri Maheshwara said: For the sake of oneself or for the sake of others, and by relying on the greatness of joy. Those men who do not lie in this world go to heaven.
For the sake of occupation or for the sake of righteousness and so on from the lustful. Those men who do not tell lies go to heaven
Her voice was soft, unhindered, sweet and sinless. Those men who go to heaven greet them with welcome
Those who do not speak harshly, bitterly and cruelly. Those pious men who are devoid of deceit go to heaven
Fools do not utter words that discriminate against friends Those men who go to heaven utter true friendship
Those human beings who avoid men and betrayal of others. Those self-controlled men equal to all beings go to heaven.
They refrain from deceitful talk and avoid the opposite. Those men who always speak gentlely will go to heaven
Those who do not utter words that pierce the heart out of anger Those men who go to heaven speak peace even when angry
O goddess this is the righteousness enjoined by men and should always be followed He is auspicious and truthful and should always be avoided by the wise.
Uma said: By the action by which a man is always bound by the mind. O most fortunate god of gods wielder of Pinaka tell me that
Sri Maheshwara said: Men are always united in Dharma by the mind in this world. O auspicious ones they go to heaven Listen to me as I relate it
A poorly crafted mind is a more poorly crafted act. O fairfaced lady listen to the words by which the mind is bound here
When you see someone else's property lying in a deserted forest. Those men who go to heaven do not harm even in their minds
Anything in a village or house that is belonging to others and is located in the desert. Those men who go to heaven do not always welcome them
Similarly, those who are lustful and secluded from other men's wives. Those men who go to heaven do not harm even in their minds
Men who are always of equal mind, enemy and friend. Those men who go to heaven worship those friends who meet them
They are obedient, compassionate, pure and truthful. Those men satisfied with their own chariots go to heaven
Those who are not hostile are always engaged in friendship Those men who are compassionate to all beings go to heaven.
They are faithful, compassionate, insightful, and dear to the insightful. Those men who are always conversant with righteousness and irreligion will go to heaven
In the accumulation of the fruits of good and evil deeds. O Devi those men who know the consequences will go to heaven
They are just and virtuous and always devoted to gods and brahmins. Those men who have attained heaven have attained to heaven
O Devi I have described these auspicious fruits of action You are devoted to the path to heaven What more do you wish to hear here
Uma said I have great doubts about some of us, O Lord. Therefore you should explain it to me today with skill
O lord how long does a man live by long action O Lord of the gods how can one attain great life even by austerities
By what action does a man on earth become short-lived? O irreproachable Lord you should tell me the consequences of my actions
Others are very fortunate and others are less fortunate Some of them were of noble birth and others of noble birth
Some of the men looked like they were made of wood Similarly other men were pleasing to the eye just by seeing them
Some seem to be foolish and some seem to be wise. The highly intelligent and also others who are conscious of knowledge and realization.
Some are minor obstacles and others are major obstacles. O lord men are visible You should explain that to me
Srimaheshwara said: Oh, I will tell you, O Devi, the rise of the fruits of action. By which every man in the world of mortals enjoys his own fruits.
He who is terrible at the risk of his life is always ready with a rod in his hand Every man with his weapon ready kills hosts of beings He is merciless and always causes anxiety to all beings. He is compassionate even to insects and ants A man thus, O goddess, goes to hell. On the contrary a righteous man is born handsome
O Devi a man who is fond of violence is to be killed by sinful deeds He who is unpleasant to all beings is born without life.
The violent soul goes to hell and the violent goes to heaven. That man undergoes terrible torment in hell
Whoever has gone out of hell will never escape from it. He attains humanity and is born there without life. O Devi a man is bound by sinful actions and is fond of violence He who is unpleasant to all beings is born without life. He who is of white descent and avoids killing animals A weapon laid down without punishment never causes harm It does not kill, it does not kill, it does not approve. With affection for all beings as for oneself so for others. Such a man's exaltation, O goddess, attains divinity. He enjoys the pleasures he has attained with joy.
And if it ever happens in the human world. That man who is born there lives a long life and prospers happily
This is the path of those who live long and are well behaved and do good deeds Uttered by Brahma for the liberation from violence against living beings
Bhishma said Thus addressed, praising this, this is the command of the supreme anger. He began to inquire this question pertaining to liberation, dharma and artha.
Shuka said: A wise, hearer, sacrificer, wise, and free from envy. How does one attain to Brahman, who has not come and is immoral?
By your age, by celibacy, by all renunciation and by intelligence. Whether in Sankhya or in Yoga, if this is inquired, tell me.
As the unity of the mind and the senses is attained. You should explain to me the means by which men can do that
Vyasa said: There is no other than knowledge and austerity, and no other than the restraint of the senses. No one attains perfection elsewhere than by renunciation of all.
All great beings are the former creation of Svayambhuva. Most of them are indwelled in the bodies in the name of the life-giving fire.
The body of the earth is the affection from the water, and the eye of the light is remembered. The air in the sky is the source of life and exhalation for embodied beings
When Vishnu is revolted, Indra wants to eat the fire in the cell. The directions of the ears are the ear, and speech is the Saraswati in the tongue.
The ear, the skin, the eyes, the tongue and the nose are the fifth. The gates mentioned by the senses of sight are for the accomplishment of food
Sound, touch, form, taste and smell are the fifth. But always knowing the objects of the senses separately from the senses.
He engages the senses and the mind, and subdues them, as horses do. And again, the Self of beings, abiding in the heart, always engages.
The mind is the Lord of the senses and also of all these. In regulation and in creation, the Self of beings and also the mind.
The senses and the sense-objects, nature, consciousness and the mind. Prana and Apana and the living entity are constantly in the bodies of the embodied.
There is no shelter, the qualities of Sattva are sound, not consciousness. For Sattva, the effulgence, never creates the alities.
Thus the seventeenth is enveloped in the body by the sixteen modes. The wise brahmin sees himself in himself by his mind.
For it is not visible to the eyes nor to all the senses. But by the lamp of the mind the great soul shines forth.
It is inexhaustible in the form of sound, touch, taste and smell. One should look at the disembodied in bodies, devoid of senses.
The unmanifest, supremely dependent on all mortal bodies. He who sees it, after death, attains to the state of Brahman.
A Brahmin endowed with knowledge and descent, a cow and an elephant. The learned are equally minded when they are pure and also when they are dog-eaters.
For He is in all beings, movable and immovable. There dwells the one great Self by whom all this is pervaded.
and the Self in all beings, and all beings in the Self. When the Self-being sees, then he attains to Brahman.
As much as the Vedic Self is in the Self, so much is the Self in the Supreme Self. He who thus constantly knows is fit for immortality.
and of the Lord, who is the Self of all beings, and the welfare of all beings. Even the gods are deluded on the path of calamity
Like birds in the sky, like fish in the water. As the movement is not seen, so is the movement of the knowers of knowledge.
Time cooks all beings in itself. But no one in this world knows the time in which time is cooking.
It is neither above it nor obliquely nor below it nor again and again Nothing is accepted in the middle nor anywhere else
All these worlds are within, and nothing of them is external. If he comes to me again and again like an arrow devoid of virtue It would not be the end of the cause, even if it were the speed of the mind. Therefore there is nothing subtler than the subtle; there is nothing grosser than that.
Hands and feet everywhere, that eyes, head and face everywhere. He who is heard everywhere in the world pervades everything and remains.
That is greater than the atom, that is greater than the great. That which is fixed within all beings remains and is not seen.
This is the dual nature of the Self, the imperishable and the imperishable. The perishable in all beings is that divine nectar, the imperishable.
Having reached the nine gates of the city the swan is always subdued He is the Lord of all beings, immovable and movable.
and by the accumulation of new loss breaking options. The transcendental say that the unborn of bodies is a swan.
The swan-spoken and the imperishable, that which is in the Kutastha, is the imperishable. That learned, having attained the imperishable, gives up the life-giving.
Nakula said O Madhava the king of righteousness has spoken many words You have heard that from a noble knower of dharma
O Madhava having understood the opinion of the king and Bhimasena The restraint and strength of the arms of the soul of Madhava have been declared.
You have heard what Phalguna said in the same way You have repeatedly related to me your heroic opinion
You have transcended all this and heard the supreme. O best among men do whatever you think the time has come
For in that and in that cause there is an opinion, O Kesava. O subduer of enemies it is proper for a man to act when the time comes
For the meaning thought otherwise becomes again that otherwise. O best of men men in this world are of impermanent minds
Otherwise it would have been wise for us dwellers in the forest Otherwise in the invisible, O Krishna, and again in the visible.
O Varshneya let us also wander in the forest There is no love in the kingdom as it is now
Heroes have come here on hearing that we have ceased to live in the forest By Thy grace, O Janardana, these seven akshauhinis have been formed.
These men are tigers of inconceivable strength and courage. Who in this world would not be distressed to see men armed with weapons in battle
That you in the midst of the Kurus, before comforting him, after fear. Let Duryodhana speak words in such a way that Manda will not be disturbed.
Yudhisthira, the terrible army of Bhimasena, was defeated. Sahadeva and also me and Thee and Rama, O Kesava. and the mighty Satyaki and Virata with their sons. And also, O Madhava, Dupada with his ministers and Dhrishtadyumna. and the mighty king of Kasi, and Dhrishtaketu, the king of Chedi. Who can fight in battle against a mortal bearing flesh and blood
That you will undoubtedly accomplish as soon as you leave. O mightyarmed one this is only the desire of the king of righteousness
Vidura, Bhishma, and Drona, with their army. O sinless one they are capable of knowing what you are saying
They will also persuade Dhritarashtra, the king of the people. And Duryodhana along with his ministers of sinful conduct
And Vidura is the hearer of the meaning, and Thou art the speaker, O Janardana. They should not keep him in armor as if he were returning for no purpose
Brihadasva said to the rivers mountains forests and lakes Soon the astronaut moved about as if he were flying in the sky
Then king Bhangasura departed in his chariot The conqueror of the enemy city saw his upper garment fallen down
Then he hurried and fell on the floor. The highminded king said to Nala 'I will seize him' O highly intelligent one restrain these swift horses O Varshneya bring this cloth to me as long as it lasts
Nala replied to him Your cloth has fallen from a distance It has traveled a distance of one yojana It cannot be retrieved
Thus addressed by Nala the king Bhangasura replied O king he came across a frightening tree in the forest bearing fruit
The king, seeing him with his arms outstretched, hurriedly addressed him. O charioteer look at my supreme strength in numbers too
Everyone does not know everything, there is no one who knows everything. There is no fixation of knowledge anywhere in the Purusha.
The leaves and fruits on this tree, my arm. There were more than one hundred others that had fallen down There is more than one leaf and one fruit with five crore arms and two crores of leaves on both branches Two branches of Prachinuguhya and other branches From these two thousand fruits two fifteen and one hundred
Then Bahuko seated the chariot and addressed the king O king destroyer of enemies you are boasting to me as if indirectly I am doing this directly, calming the horror. O king there is no indirection in mathematics O great king I shall appease your fear directly I do not know whether this will happen or not
O lord of men I shall count the fruits of this tree while you are watching Let the son of Varshneya give the rays of the horses even for a moment
The king told the charioteer that it was not time to delay Bahuka with great effort replied Wait a moment or you'll be in a hurry. This is the auspicious path that the charioteer of Varshneya is going on
"O descendant of the Kurus" said Dutuparna consoling him You alone are the controller and there is none else on earth, O arm.
I wish to go to Vidarbha for your sake I am expert in horses I take refuge in you You should not hinder me
And I will do whatever you tell me, my arm. If you go to Vidarbha today you will show me the Sun
Then Bahuka said to him 'Count me frightening' Then I shall go to Vidarbha Do as I say
The king said to him as if he were unwilling to count him O sinless one I have also indicated a place for the branch Count it, O knower of the truth of the horse, and then you will be pleased. He got down from the chariot and quickly killed the tail
Then, filled with wonder, he said to the king. Counting the fruits as mentioned above
O king I have seen your strength which is most wonderful O King I wish to hear about the knowledge by which this is known Then the king said to him O king as I was leaving in haste Know Me to be the sacrificer of the heart of the Aksha and an expert in numbers.
Bahukas said to him, "Give me this knowledge. O best among men accept my heart too
Then the king, Rituparna, out of respect for his duty, lifted his arm. Out of greed for knowledge of the horse she said to him 'So be it'
Take this supreme heart of the axes as you have said Let the arms of my horse rest on you Having said this Amritaparna gave the knowledge to Nala
Kali flowed from the body of that axis-heart sacrificer. He constantly vomited sharp cancer venom from his mouth The fire of the curse emanated from that afflicted Kali The selfless king was exhausted by this for a long time
Then Kali, freed from the poison, assumed his form. Nala king of Nishadha in anger wanted to curse him
Trembling with folded hands Kalito addressed him O king control your anger I shall bestow upon you supreme fame
Indrasena's mother was angry and killed him in the past When you abandoned me I was greatly distressed
I have stayed with you, O king, in great pain, undefeated. He was burning day and night with the venom of the king of serpents
I take refuge in you, hear my words! And those men in the world who will praise you without laziness. Their fear born of me will never arise I have taken refuge in fear if you do not curse me Thus addressed king Nala controlled his anger
Then frightened Kali quickly entered the frightening place Kali was invisible to others while Naishadha was talking about it
Then king Naishadha the destroyer of enemy heroes recovered from his fever In the Age of Kali the king will be destroyed Endowed with supreme joy and splendor with the other Brilliant Rama mounted his chariot and set out on swift horses
Bibhitaka is also unpraiseworthy and has turned away from the refuge of Kali. Like brahmins he rode again and again on the best of horses Nala urged him with a delighted inner self. The illustrious king set out for Vidarbha
When they had crossed the pipe, Kali also went home. Then king Nala relieved of his fever became lord of the earth O King I was liberated from Kali and separated from my form
Pulastya said O best of kings thereafter one should go to the praised Kurukshetra Where all beings are freed from sins by seeing Him.
I will go to Kurukshetra and I will stay in Kurukshetra. He who thus constantly recites is liberated from all sins.
Even the dust was blown away by the wind at Kurukshetra Do they lead to the supreme destination for those who have committed evil deeds
Saraswati on the south and Drishadvati on the north Those who dwell in Kurukshetra dwell in heaven.
There, O Yudhisthira, the brave man should live in Saraswati for a month. Where Brahma and other gods, sages, Siddhas and Charanas reside.
O king gandharvas apsaras yakshas and serpents They reach the most sacred Brahmakshetra, O Arjuna.
Kurukshetra is the place of desire even in the mind, O Yudhisthira. Sins are destroyed and he attains the world of Brahman.
O best of the Kurus having reached Kurukshetra with faith Then he obtains the fruits of Rajasuya and Asvamedha
Then there was a mighty gatekeeper named Mankhanaka One who offers obeisances to a yaksha obtains the fruits of a thousand cows
Then one who knows righteousness should go to the supreme abode of Visnu O Indra among kings there is a place called Satata where Lord Hari resides
Having bathed there and offered obeisances to Hari the origin of the three worlds He obtains the Asvamedha and goes to the world of Visnu. Then one should go to Pariplava a holy place famous in the three worlds He obtains the fruits of Agnistoma and Atiratra, O Arjuna.
One who reaches the holy place of the earth obtains the fruits of a thousand cows. O king thereafter Shalukini who served holy places went there And he who takes a bath in the Dashashwamedha obtains the same fruit. Having reached the goddess of snakes an excellent holy place for serpents He attains the Agnistomas and attains the world of serpents. Then knower of dharma go to the gatekeeper who is swimming One who stays there for one night will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows Then he went to Panchanada and ate regularly One who touches Kotitirtha obtains the fruits of Hayamedha. Having reached the holy place of Aśvinī-kumāra he is born beautiful
Then one who knows righteousness should go to the excellent holy place of Varaha Where Lord Visnu in the form of Varaha resided in the past One who bathes there, O best of men, obtains the fruits of the Agnistomas.
O best of kings thereafter on the day of Jayanti one should enter Somatirtha After bathing, a human being obtains the fruits of Rajasuya.
A man who bathes in a single swan obtains the fruits of a thousand cows. O lord of men a worshiper of holy places having performed purification He obtains Pundarika and becomes purified.
Then there is the place of the great sage Sthanu called Munjavata One who fasts for one night attains Ganapati status.
O great king there was also a yakshini renowned in the world O Indra among kings one who takes his bath and approaches him obtains all his desires
That gate of Kurukshetra is well known, O best of the Bharatas. A worshiper of holy places having circumambulated the place with concentration O noble gods of the ancestors bathe in the lakes measured That great soul Rama son of Jamadagni performed this ritual O king he will be accomplished in his duties and will obtain a horse sacrifice Thereafter a worshiper of holy places should go to Rama's lake with concentration
O best of kings there Rama with his eagerness burning with effulgence The heroic Rama destroyed the kshatriyas and settled in five lakes
O tiger among men it is well known that he filled it with blood All the fathers and grandfathers were satisfied
O king the fathers were pleased and said to Rama
The fathers said O Rama O most fortunate Bhrigu we are pleased with you O lord you have shown this devotion to your father and your prowess O effulgent lady ask for a boon May you prosper What do you desire
Pulastya said O Indra among kings Rama the best of strikers was thus addressed With folded palms he addressed his ancestors who were seated in the sky If you are pleased with me, please invite me. I desire the grace of my father to perform austerities and drink water again
And that I have destroyed the Kshatriyas in my anger. Then by your effulgence I shall be freed from sin The lakes should become holy places for me and become famous on earth
The parents of Rama heard these auspicious words O Rama they replied with great delight and joy May your austerities especially your devotion to your father increase again
And that you have destroyed the Kshatriyas in anger. Then you are freed from sin You have fallen down by your own actions
There is no doubt that the lakes will become your holy places Whoever takes a bath in those lakes will satisfy his ancestors His fathers will be pleased to give him what is rare on earth The desires of the mind and the eternal world of heaven
O king Rama's parents thus granted him boons Having taken leave of Bhrigu with affection they disappeared from there
Thus the killing of Rama by the great Bhrigu was pious Having bathed in the hearts of auspicious Rama he observed celibacy O best of kings one who worships Rama will obtain a lot of gold O best of the Kurus having attained the root of his dynasty he served holy places
O king one should take a bath at the root of the lineage and raise his own lineage O best of the Bharatas having reached a holy place for purification of the body There is no doubt that one who bathes in that holy place purifies his body And with a pure body he attains to the auspicious and excellent worlds.
Then one who knows righteousness should go to a holy place renowned in the three worlds Where the worlds were formerly raised by the all-powerful Visnu. Having attained the salvation of the worlds, the holy place is worshiped in the three worlds. Kings who bathe in the best of holy places save their own worlds
Having reached Sritirtha and taken a bath with a steady mind Having worshiped the ancestors and gods he attains supreme prosperity.
Having reached Kapilatirtha, he observed celibacy and concentrated. Having bathed there he worshiped his ancestors and his gods A man obtains the fruits of a thousand Kapilas.
Having reached a holy place known as Suryatirtha he took his bath with a restrained mind After worshiping the ancestors and gods he observed a fast He obtains the Agni-Stoma and goes to the world of the Sun.
The pilgrims reached the cowshed in order. One who performs abhishekam there obtains the fruits of a thousand cows
O best of the Kurus, having reached Shankhinitirtha, he was a holy worshipper. A man who takes a bath in this holy place of the goddess attains excellent beauty
Then, O king of kings, go to the gatekeeper, Marantaka. That great lord of yakshas (Rama) is a holy place on the river Saraswati A man who bathes there, O king, obtains the fruits of the Agnistomas.
O best of kings the best of men should then go to Brahmavarta A man who takes a bath in Brahmavarta attains the Brahmaloka.
O Indra among kings thereafter one should proceed to an excellent holy place The ancestors along with the gods are always present there One who is engaged in worship of the ancestors and gods should perform abhisheka there He attains the Ashwamedha and goes to the world of the ancestors.
O knower of righteousness there is an excellent holy place called Ambumati
O best of Bharatas having bathed in the holy places of Lord Kashi Freed from all diseases he attains to the world of Brahman.
And the mother's holy place is there where one takes a bath, O Bharatha. O king the people are increasing in number and are enjoying prosperity
Then one should go to Sitavan and eat regularly O great king there is a great holy place rarely found anywhere else
It purifies one who has seen it since he left, O lord of men. One who dries his hair in that water is purified, O Arjuna.
O great king there is a holy place there which is said to remove the hair of dogs O best among men learned brahmins devoted to holy places reside there They attain supreme pleasure after bathing, O best of the Bharatas. O best of the Bharatas at a holy place where Vavilloma was removed The best of the brahmins remove their hair by pranayama. O best of kings those whose souls are purified attain the supreme state
O king the ten horse sacrifices were also performed at that holy place O tiger among men one who takes bath there will attain the supreme state
O best of kings thereafter he should go to a human being renowned in the world O king where the black deer was tormented by the arrows of the hunter They dived into that lake and became human. A man who observes celibacy with concentration after bathing in that holy place
He who is purified of all sins is glorified in the heavenly world. O lord of the earth it is only a krosa east of Manusha The famous river called Aapga is served by the Siddhas. The man who offers blackberries for food there. The fruit of his righteousness is great in addressing the gods and fathers. If one brahmin is fed a crore are fed
Having bathed there and worshiped the ancestors and gods One who stays for one night obtains the fruits of Agnistomas
O best of kings thereafter one should go to the best abode of Brahma Brahmodumbara is the light on earth, O Arjuna.
O best of men there he bathed in the pools of the seven sages O Indra among kings also at Kedara where great Kapila lived Then, having attained Brahman, he became pure and concentrated. He whose soul is purified of all sins attains to the world of Brahman. And it is very rare to reach Kedar for Kapila. He whose sins have been burnt by austerities attains disappearance
O king of kings from there go to Saraka famous in the world On the fourteenth day of the dark fortnight he approached Vrishadhvaja He obtains all his desires and goes to heaven
O descendant of the Kurus there are three crore holy places in Saraka
O king in Rudrakoti and in wells and lakes O best of the Bharatas there is also a holy place called Ilaspada There you should bathe and worship the gods and ancestors He never attains misfortune nor obtains Vajapeya.
O king a man takes a bath in Kindan and in Kinjapy He attains immeasurable charity and chanting, O Arjuna.
With faith and self-control he touched the water in the pitcher. Man obtains the fruits of the sacrifice of Agnistoma.
The great sage Narada lived on the east side of Saraka O best of the Kurus this holy place is wellknown as Ambajanma
There, in a holy place, a man takes a bath and gives up his life, O Bharatha. Permitted by Narada he attains the supreme worlds
On the tenth day of the white fortnight one should enter Pundiraka O King one who takes bath there obtains the fruits of lotus flowers
Then he will go to heaven, famous in the three worlds. There is a holy river Vaitarani destroyer of sins
There he bathed and worshiped the bull flag holding a spear. Let him, purified of all sins, attain to the Supreme Goal.
Then, O king of kings, go to the excellent fruit forest. O King there the gods always take refuge in the forest of fruit trees They practice vast austerities for many thousands of years A man takes his bath in Drishadvati and satisfies the gods Agnistoma obtains the fruits of the two nights, O Bharatha. O best of the Bharatas having bathed in a holy place for all the gods O king of kings a man obtains the fruits of a thousand cows A man who takes his bath in the pit of his hands and satisfies the gods Agnistoma obtains the fruits of the two nights, O Bharatha. He obtains Rajasuya and attains the world of the sages.
Then, O king of kings, one should go to the excellent holy place of Misraka. O best of kings there are holy places mixed with great souls O tiger among kings we have heard that Vyasa said this for the sake of brahmins He who takes a bath in all holy places takes a bath in a mixed river
Then he should go to Vyasavana and there he should eat regularly A man who takes a bath at the speed of his mind obtains the fruits of a thousand cows
A man who goes to Madhuvati and the holy place of the goddess is purified. A man bathes there and worships the ancestors and gods. With the permission of the goddess he will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows
He who was born at the confluence of Kausiki and Drishadvati, O Arjuna. He who takes a bath and eats regularly is freed from all sins.
Then there was a place called Vyasasthali by the intelligent Vyasa. Tormented by the grief of his son he decided to give up his body O Indra among kings thereafter the gods raised him up again He will reach the ground and get the fruits of a thousand cows.
He reached the well given to him and offered him sesame seeds He shall attain supreme perfection, freed from debt, O best of the Kurus. A man who takes a bath in a holy place known as Vedi will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows
Aha and Sudin are two holy places renowned in the world By bathing in them, O tiger among men, he attains the world of the sun.
Then one should go to the deer smoke which is famous in the three worlds O best of kings one should perform abhisheka there in Ganga
One who worships Mahadeva obtains the fruits of Ashwamedha. A man who takes a bath in a holy place of the goddess will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows
Then one should go to Vamana famous in the three worlds Having bathed there at the feet of Visnu and worshiped Vamana He whose soul is purified of all sins attains the world of Vishnu. A man who takes a bath in the Kulampuna purifies his own family thereafter
Having taken a bath in the lake of the wind it is an excellent holy place for the Maruts O tiger among men one who bathes there is attained to the world of Visnu
Having bathed in the lake of the immortals he worshiped the king of the immortals By the power of the immortals he is glorified in the world of heaven.
and in the holy place of Shalihotra and in the Shali Surya in accordance with the ordinance. O best among men one who takes bath will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows
And Sri Kuzha, the holy place of Saraswati, O best of the Bharatas. O best among men one who takes bath there obtains the fruits of Agnistomas
Then, O chief of the Kurus, reach Naimishakujha. O best of kings there are indeed ascetics from Naimisha In the past they went to Kurakshetra in advance of a pilgrimage O best of the Bharatas thereafter a lotus flower was made for the river Saraswati
There would be a great opportunity for the sages to be as satisfying A man who bathes in that pool obtains the fruits of the Agnistomas.
Then one who knows righteousness should go to the excellent Kanyatirtha A man who takes a bath in Kanyatirtha will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows
O best of kings thereafter one should go to the best holy place of Brahma A man of lower castes bathes there and attains brahminhood And a Brahmin with a pure mind will attain the Supreme Goal.
O best among men one should then proceed to the excellent Somatirtha A man who bathes there, O king, attains the Somaloka.
O King thereafter one should go to Saptasarasvata holy place There is a great sage named Mankanaka who is famous in the world O king we have heard that in the past the beads were made of kusacha O king his hand was wounded and his vegetable juice flowed He danced in delight at the sight of Shakarasa
Then in that dance, however, whatever is movable and immovable. O hero both of them danced bewildered by his effulgence
Brahma and other gods and royal sages rich in asceticism. O Mahadeva O lord of men this was informed by the sage
O lord you should do as he should not dance I was overjoyed to find him dancing. O sage for the welfare of the gods Lord Brahma addressed them
O great sage knower of righteousness why are you dancing O preeminent among ascetics why is this place of joy for you today
The sage said O best of brahmins you are an ascetic who is on the path of righteousness O Brahman why do you not see the sugar flowing from my hand Seeing him I danced with great joy
"O lord of the sages deluded by passion Rama laughed and said
O brahmin look at me I am not going to be amazed O best among men thus addressed by wise Mahadeva O sinless king of kings his thumb was struck by the chain of his fingers O king ashes resembling snow came out of the wound
Seeing this, O king, the sage fell at his feet in distress. He thought of nothing greater than God and greater than Rudra.
You are the destination of the world of gods and demons, bearer of a spear. Thou hast created all this three worlds moving and unmoving.
You alone chase them all again at the end of the age. Even the gods cannot know you Why should I not know you
O sinless one all the gods Brahma and others are seen in you Thou art the creator and causer of all the worlds.
By your grace all the gods rejoice here without fear Having thus praised Mahadevabhushi said
O Mahadeva by your grace my austerities will not be wasted Then the delighted god said to the brahmarshi
O brahmin may your austerities increase in a thousand ways by my grace O great ascetic I shall stay with you in this hermitage
But those who will bathe in the seven Sarasvatis and worship Me. Nothing is difficult for them in this world or in the next
And they will undoubtedly go to the world of Saraswati. Having said this Mahadeva disappeared from there
Then one should go to Usanasa famous in the three worlds where Brahma and other gods and sages rich in asceticism reside
And Lord Kartikeya, indeed, for three evenings, O Bharatha. Desiring to please Bhrigu he kept his presence daily
The skull-releasing holy place is the redemption of all sins. O tiger among men one who takes bath there is freed from all sins
O best of men one should then go to Agnitirtha and take a bath there He attains the world of fire and also uplifts his family.
O best of Bharatas there is a holy place of Viswamitra O best among men one who takes bath there attains brahminhood
Having attained the Brahma-yoga, he is pure and of an attentive mind. O tiger among men one who bathes there attains the world of Brahma He also purifies the seventh dynasty, there is no doubt about it.
O best of kings thereafter one should go to a holy place renowned in the three worlds O king it is known as Pruthudaka of Kartikeya One who is engaged in worship of the ancestors and gods should perform abhisheka there
Whether by ignorance or knowledge, by a woman or a man. Any evil deed committed by a man of human intelligence All that is destroyed by one who bathes there, O Bharatha. He attains the fruits of an ashwamedha and the world of heaven
They say that Kurukshetra is holy and from Kurukshetra Saraswati. There are holy places on the river Saraswati and abundant water from the holy places
He who renounces his own body is the best of all holy places. One who chants this mantra in broad waters will not suffer death tomorrow
Sung by Sanatkumara and the great Vyasa. O King in this way he should reach the broad waters as prescribed
There is no holy place more holy than Pruthudaka, O leader of the Kurus. That is impure, that is sacred and purifying, there is no doubt.
Those who have committed sins bathe there and go to heaven O best among men so say the sages in the broad waters
O best of Bharatas there is also a holy place called Madhusrava O King one who takes bath there will obtain the fruits of a thousand cows
O best of kings thereafter one should proceed to the sacrificial holy places in order The confluence of the rivers Saraswati and Aruna is famous in the world
After fasting for three nights and taking a bath he is freed from the sin of killing a brahmin Man obtains the fruits of Agnistoma and Atiratra. It also purifies the seventh dynasty, O best of the Bharatas.
O chief of the Kuru dynasty there is also a holy place called Ardhakeela It was made of darbha in the past to show mercy to the brahmins Even by observing vows and observing fasts There is no doubt that he is a Brahmin accompanied by rituals and mantras O best among men a learned man who takes a bath there without performing ritualistic ceremonies and chanting ritualistic ceremonies will have broken his vows This has been seen by the ancients
The four seas were also brought together by Darbha O best among men one who follows them will not suffer misfortune He also gets the fruits of four thousand cows.
O knower of righteousness one should then go to a hundred thousand holy places There are two holy places famous in the world for a thousand holy places A man who bathes in both obtains the fruits of a thousand cows Charity or fasting should be multiplied a thousand times
O best of kings thereafter one should proceed to the excellent Renukatirtha One should perform holy abhisheka and be engaged in worship of the ancestors and gods. He whose soul is purified of all sins obtains the fruits of the Agni-Stoma.
Having touched liberation he conquered anger and conquered his senses He is freed from all the evils committed by accepting charity
Then he went to Panchavati and observed celibacy and conquered his senses Endowed with great merit he is glorified in the world of the virtuous.
Where the Lord of Yoga stands, Himself the bull-flag. By worshiping him lord of the gods it is accomplished by departure
The effulgent Varuna holy place is glowing with its own effulgence. where Brahma and other gods and sages rich in asceticism resided Then Guha was consecrated by the gods as commander of the army O best of the Kurus there is a holy place known as Kurutirtha on the eastern side of Taijasa
A man who takes a bath in Kurutirtha and observes celibacy and has conquered his senses He whose soul is purified of all sins attains to the world of Brahman.
Then one who eats regularly should go to the gate of heaven He attains the world of heaven and goes to the world of Brahma.
Then, O lord of men, a worshiper of holy places will go to hell. O king a man who takes bath there will not suffer misfortune O lord of the earth Brahma himself is always there with the gods O tiger among men he is being followed by the men led by Narayana
O best of kings O best of the Kurus there is the presence of Rudrapalya One who reaches that goddess will not suffer any misfortune
O great king there also I worship Lord Uma the lord of the universe Having reached Mahadeva one is freed from all sins.
Narayana also approached this lotus-naveled enemy. O great king as a king he attains the world of Visnu O best of men he took his bath in the holy places of all the gods Abandoned by all sorrows a man shines like the Moon
Then, O lord of men, the pilgrim should go to Swastipura. One who circumambulates the place obtains the fruits of a thousand cows
One should reach a holy holy place and satisfy the gods of the ancestors He obtains the fruits of the sacrifice of Agnistoma, O Arjuna.
O best of the Bharatas there is also a lake of Ganga and a well O king there are three crore holy places in that well
A man who bathes there, O king, attains heaven. A man who takes a bath in the river Afga and worships Lord Mahadeva He attains Ganapati status and saves his family.
Then one should go to Sthanuvata wellknown in the three worlds One who takes a bath there and stays there at night attains the world of Rudra
Then one should go to the hermitage of Vasishta for cooking badari trees A man who has fasted for three nights should eat badari there He who eats badari trees for twelve years If he fasts for three nights he will be equal to it, O lord of men. O lord of men he reached the path of Rudra and served holy places By fasting day and night he is glorified in the world of Indra.
A man who arrives for one night and stays there for one night He who is determined and truthful is glorified in the world of Brahman.
O best of kings thereafter one should go to a holy place renowned in the three worlds There is the hermitage of the great soul Aditya who resides in the host of effulgence Anyone who takes bath in that holy place and worships Vibhavasu He goes to the world of the sun and saves his family.
O lord of men a man who takes his bath in Somatirtha should serve holy places A man attains the world of the moon, there is no doubt about it.
Then knower of dharma go to the great soul Dadhīci O king it is a most holy and sacred holy place renowned in the world Where Sarasvata went that Angira was the treasure of austerities.
