He is always protected by me and is always self-reliant. How could the forest dwellers knowing the curse have passed you by
Surely you should protect the king of men O Madri How did you lure the king in this desolate place
How can a poor man always find you in seclusion Thinking about the curse he was delighted
Blessed are you outwardly and more fortunate than I am. You have seen the face of the king who is delighted
"O goddess while I was crying and repeatedly forbidden by me Manyu said His desire to fulfill his destiny was not prevented by him
Kunti said I am the eldest wife of righteousness and the eldest fruit of righteousness is mine O Madri do not dissuade me from feelings which are certainly coming I am looking for my husband here I am under the control of a dead man Get up and leave him and take care of these daughters I am greedy for having sons and I want to be the wife of a hero.
Manyu said I alone will follow my husband who has not fled I am not satisfied with all my desires O eldest one accept me
And this best of Bharatas, having approached me, is exhausted from lust. How can we cut off his desire in the abode of Yama
Nor am I treating your sons without distinction. O noble lady I shall go about my occupation Let him touch me in the same way
Therefore Kunti should treat my daughters like their own sons Desirous of me this king has fallen under the sway of the dead
Vaishampayana said: This body of mine is also with the body of the king. O noble lady please me with this wellcovered body which is to be burnt
Be careful with my daughters and be good to me Therefore I do not see anything else to be commanded
Vaishampayana said Having said this to the best of men who was in the funeral pyre the wife of righteousness The illustrious daughter of the king of Madras at once ascended the mountain
Vaishampayana said Then Bhishma, the young man of peace, addressed Duryodhana in anger. On hearing the words of Kesava, O best of the Bharatas, he replied:
You have been addressed by Krishna wishing peace to your friends O dear follow him Do not follow him under the control of anger
O dear child I have not obeyed the words of the great soul Kesava You will never attain prosperity, happiness or prosperity.
O dear son the mightyarmed Kesava has spoken to you for the sake of righteousness O king do not let the subjects approach you for that purpose
You have burnt this Lakshmi Bharati among all the kings. You will destroy Dhritarashtra while he is still alive because of his evil spirit.
Myself along with my ministers my sons brothers and relatives You will be destroyed from life by thinking 'I am'
Going beyond the facts of Keshav's words meaningfully. O best of the Bharatas also to his father the sagacious Vidura
Don't be a destroyer of the family, a wicked man, a wicked man, and go down the path of cowardice. Do not drown in the ocean of sorrow for your mother and father
Then Drona said these words to Duryodhana there. Overcome with indignation he was sighing again and again
O dear Kesava has spoken to you words in accordance with righteousness and meaning Thus, O King, enjoy Bhishma, the young man of peace.
They were wise, intelligent, self-controlled, eager for wealth and well- educated. O king enjoy the words they have spoken to you in your favor
Stand still, O greatly wise one, as Krishna and Bhishma said. Do not despise Madhava by delusion of intellect, O scorcher of enemies.
Those who encourage you are never for action They will release their enmity from the necks of others in battle
May all the people, their sons and brothers not live. Wherever Vasudeva and Arjuna are known, fire conquers them.
This also is the true opinion of the friends Krishna and Bhishma. If thou wilt not give, O dear one, afterwards thou shalt suffer, O Arjuna.
As said by the son of Jamadagni, this greater then Arjuna. For Krishna, the son of Devakī, is very unbearable even to the gods. O best of the Bharatas what is the use of this statement by you who are dear to happiness
I have told you all this, do as you please. O best of the Bharatas I do not wish to speak to you any more
Vaishampayana said In the midst of that sentence, Kshatriya Vidura also spoke. Beholding Duryodhana, the indignant king of Dhritarashtra.
Duryodhana, O best of the Bharatas, I do not grieve for you. I am grieving for these aged Gandhari and your father
It is difficult for you to keep the two orphans alone They were like eggs with salt wings destroyed their friends and ministers destroyed
A monk will wander about this earth mourning Having produced such a sinful man who is destroyer of the family
Then King Dhritarashtra addressed Duryodhana. I was seated with my brothers surrounded by kings
Duryodhana, listen to what the great sage Sauri has said. Take hold of that most auspicious, inexhaustible Yoga-safety.
For with the help of this Krishna of effortless action. We shall obtain all the desires of all kings
Well arranged by Kesava, my dear, go to Yudhisthira. Go forth auspicious and healthy for all the sons of Bharata
O dear son go to peace by the holy place of Vasudeva I think it is time Do not go beyond Duryodhana
If you ask for peace, you will reject Kesava. There is no defeat for you who speak for your sake
Bhishma said: Pulling the bow, destroying the enemy, agriculture, trade and raising cattle. Service also for the sake of the same is the supreme duty of a brahmin
But the sixfold Brahman should be served by a householder and a wise man. It is recommended for a brahmin who has accomplished his objective to live in the forest
The king's messenger, the wealth of agriculture, and the life of the merchant. One should avoid Kautilya, Kaulateya and Kusida.
A Sudra, O king, becomes a Brahmin friend 1and a character who is devoid of Dharma. He who is the husband of a śūdra is a crooked dancer and a servant of the king is inactive
He who chants the Vedas and chants them, O king, is equal to the heroes and is to be enjoyed like a slave. All these, O King, are equal to Sudras; one should avoid them in the service of the gods.
and in the unlimited, in the unclean, in the cruel conduct, in the violent, in the abandoned religion. Havyam kavyam and whatever else, O king. They are to be given and other things are to be given to him.
Therefore, O king, restraint, purity and uprightness are the prescribed duties of a Brahmin. O King in the past all the hermitages of brahmins were abandoned
He who is self-controlled, soma-pascharya, compassionate, tolerant of all, and hopeless. That brahmin is straightforward gentle cruel forgiving and no one else commits sinful deeds
Sudras, Vaisyas and princes ruled all the worlds, desiring righteousness. Therefore, O son of Arjuna, Visnu, considering them to be attached to the duties of peace of castes, does not desire them.
If this were not the case in the world, there would be no fourfold religion and no Vedic arguments. All sacrifices and rituals performed in all the worlds should be performed at once in the hermitage
And whoever of the three castes desires to attend the hermitage. And hear, O Arjuna, those dharmas which are like the four hermitages.
I have served you, you have done your work, you have done your children's work. O lord of the world a sudra with the king's permission Even if he is in a short distance or in the ten dharmas. All hermitages were established except those without hope
Then the followers of that righteousness told him about his practice of begging O best of kings the same is true of a vaisya and also of a prince
The king's age has passed and he has worked hard. Permitted by the king a vaisya went to the hermitage
O sinless one, you should study the Vedas and the scriptures of kings according to religious principles. Having performed rituals like procreation and worshiping the moon He ruled all the people and was the best of speakers in righteousness. Rajasuya Asvamedha and other sacrifices were also performed He brought them and gave alms to the brahmins according to the recitation Having won a battle whether little or much Having established his son as the ruler of the people and in the kingdom, O Arjuna. O best of kshatriyas a kshatriya of another clan or a praiseworthy one Having worshiped the ancestors properly with the sacrifices of the ancestors in accordance with the ordinance Having worshiped the gods by sacrifices and the sages by the Vedas with great effort. And when the end comes, whoever wishes to change the hermitage. O King he will go to the hermitages in succession and attain perfection
O best of kings by being a royalty and not by serving almsgiving Even the duties of a destitute householder should be practiced for the sake of survival
And this is not a faithful act of the three, O greatly charitable one. O tiger among kings it is said that there are four inhabitants of the hermitage
It was raised by the arms of the Kshatriyas who practiced the best of the worlds Dharma among men. I hear from the Vedas that all dharmas and sub-dharmas are due to the duty of the king
As, O king, the feet of an elephant merge, the feet of all beings. Thus listen to all the duties merged in the duties of kings in all circumstances
Men who know the Dharma say that other Dharma are of little dependence and little fruit. The noble ones declare that the Kshatriya Dharma is the great shelter and the form of many auspiciousness and no other.
All religions are predominantly royal and all castes are observed. All renunciation in the duties of a king, O King, is said to be the foremost and ancient duty.
Let the Trinity sink into the ethics of punishment, and when it is killed, all righteousness will perish, O enlightened ones. If a kshatriya abandons the ancient duties of a king all the religious duties of hermitages will be destroyed
All renunciations are seen in the royal duties, and all initiations are said to be in the royal duties. All knowledge is engaged in the duties of a king All the worlds have entered into the duties of a king
as living beings are killed by ordinary men for the oppression of those who have heard the Dharma. Thus the religions are separated from the royal religion. Those who accumulate do not respect their own duty.
Vaishampayana said: But while Bhishma, the son of Dhritarashtra, was fleeing, leaving the head of the battle. The great soul released Ketu and roared and drew his bow and reached Arjuna
He saw Arjuna, the mighty warrior of the terrible bow, marching in the host of the enemy. He struck him in the middle of the forehead with a spear driven by the full length of his ear.
He was well-controlled by the golden tip of the arrow devoted to him O king the great deed shone like a beautiful single horn of a single parrot
Pierced by his arrow a hot stream of blood appeared The golden river flower pierced his forehead and shone brightly
Duryodhana also, who was of fierce splendour, and Partha, Duryodhana alone, was a hero. The two mighty warriors approached each other equally
Then he was again distorted by a huge elephant that looked like a mountain Then he ran after Jisnu son of Kunti in four chariots accompanied by elephants and foot soldiers
Arjuna, the lord of the elephants, hurriedly attacked him in the middle of the pot section. With great speed he struck him with a huge iron arrow filled with ears
Created by Partha, the cow-leaf entered the serpent from the country of Apula. Like thunderbolt created by Indra he tore through the great mountain
Burnt by the arrows the king of serpents trembled and was distressed He fell down on me in agony like the peak of a mountain struck by a thunderbolt
Vikarna suddenly descended in terror to the ground when the great tooth was dropped At once he walked eight hundred paces and got into the chariot of twenty
He killed the serpent with his arrow which looked like a thunderbolt and resembled a mountain cloud. With an arrow of the same kind, Arjuna pierced Duryodhana in the chest.
Then the elephant and the king were broken and broken and the legs were protected. The chiefs of the warriors arrived at once
On seeing the serpent killed by Partha and hearing all the warriors running away. The hero of the Kurus sealed his chariot and fled from the battle where Arjuna was not.
Duryodhana, who was in a terrible appearance, fled at once, was attacked by the enemy. The crown of the warrior's mind exploded as he vomited blood as he was struck by the arrow.
Arjuna said: Why do you flee, leaving behind abundant fame and glory, turning away from battle? Similarly your musical instruments have not been struck today since you were deposed from the kingdom
I am Yudhisthira's commander, Partha, the third, engaged in battle. Therefore, O son of Dhritarashtra, cover your mouth and give it to me. Remember the history of the king.
In vain is your name on earth, Duryodhana, which you have done here before. For you have no Duryodhananess here, fleeing from the battlefield.
I see neither before nor behind thee, O Duryodhana, the protector. Get out of battle, O hero among men; save now the dear lives of the Pandavas.
The teacher said: There are four kinds of beings, movable and immovable. They say that they have unmanifest origins and unmanifest deaths. The mind consisting of the unmanifest Self should be known to have the characteristics of the unmanifest.
It is like a huge tree inside a peach tree The manifest is seen to have emerged from the unmanifest, and also the origin.
It rushes at him as if he were unconscious Beings born of the cause of nature, as well as anything else.
Similarly, the unmanifest emotions are the cause and effect of the doer. Unconscious she was overwhelmed by the cause of the awakener
Neither the earth, nor the sky, nor the heavens, nor the beings, nor the sages, nor the gods, nor the demons. There was no other life except that which was not destroyed
Formerly, eternally omnipresent, uncharacteristic of the cause of the mind. This is the characteristic of the cause indicated by the action of ignorance.
For those reasons combined are the cause of the collection of works. By which this great wheel, the beginning of death, is moving.
The unmanifest navel, the manifest, the circle of transformations. The wheel with affectionate eyes is certainly moving among the knowers of the field
Because of its grease, the world is tormented in this wheel like a liver. Pleasures born of ignorance overpowered him like sesame seeds
He does that action out of thirst and out of egotism. That is the cause of the combination of cause and effect.
The cause does not approach the action and the action is not the cause. Time is the causal factor in the accomplishment of tasks.
Natures and transformations are caused by each other. They always revolve around each other, dominated by men.
Endowed with Rajasic and Tamasic emotions and endowed with the force of reason. Just as dust blown by the wind follows the knower of the field
Nor is it touched by those emotions nor by that great soul. There should be no dust or dust like the wind
Thus the wise should know this difference between the knower of the field of Sattva. By practice he is thus engaged and does not go back to nature.
The divine sage dispelled this doubt that had arisen. The news should be considered in accordance with the characteristics
Seeds burnt by fire do not germinate as they do again. Thus by afflictions burnt by knowledge the Self is attained again.
Bhishma said: Then, in the past great Kalpa, the son of Angirasa was born. The gods were satisfied with the birth of the priest of the gods
The words Brihad Brahma and Maha are synonymous. O King the learned Brihaspati is endowed with these virtues
Vasu, an eloquent attendant of the king, became his disciple. Then he thoroughly studied the scriptures known as Chitrashikhandija
That king was previously thought to be Vasu by destiny He ruled the earth like an unbroken heaven
There was a great sacrifice performed by that great sage Ashwamedha Brihaspati the priest became the priest there
Three of the sons of Prajapati became members of the assembly The great sages are on one side, two and three. Then Dhanusha and Raibhya and Arvavasu and Paravasu. And also the great sage Medhatithi and also Taṇḍya. The sage Shanti, the greatly fortunate, and the head of the Vedas. Kapila the best of ascetics is said to be the father of Śalihotra The first was Katha and Taittiri, the ancestor of Vaishampayana. Then Kanva and Devahotra these sixteen are mentioned.
O king all the preparations for that great sacrifice were ready There was no killing of animals The king remained silent
He is non-violent, pure, petty, hopeless, and praised for his actions. Parts of the forest footprints were arranged there
Then the ancient lord of the gods was pleased with him He showed himself to him invisible to anyone else
He himself smelled his portion and took the offering. The invisible god of monkey intelligence had taken away his share
Brihaspati then became furious and hurriedly raised the ladle. The ladle burning in the sky shed tears of anger as it fell
He said to the attendant I have prepared this part He is undoubtedly acceptable to me directly by the god himself
Yudhisthira said: The shares of the sacrifice which have been raised have been directly obtained by the gods here. Why has the mighty monkey not come here to see you
Bhishma said Then that great Vasu, the ruler of the earth, who had arisen. The sage appeased the members of the assembly in all respects
They said to him without hesitation You should not be angry In Kritayuga it is not right for you to indulge in anger
Arosana is the god whose share this is ready. O Brihaspati it is not possible for you or us to see him
He who shows mercy to him deserves to see him Then the chitrashikhandis scattered one by one spoke
For we are declared to be the sons of Brahma, the mental. Once they went to the northern direction for their own welfare
After performing austerities for thousands of years he performed excellent austerities They stood on one leg and were perfectly composed like a piece of wood.
The northern part of mount Meru is in favor of the Milky Way. That is the place where we performed extremely dreadful austerities
How can we see the God in the form of Narayana? That eternal God of gods bestows excellent boons How can we see the Lord Narayana? Then in the avabhritha of the vow the disembodied woman spoke O lord she is delightful with her affectionate and deep words
O brahmins he performed austerities with a cheerful inner self You devotees who are curious how will you see that Lord?
To the north of the ocean of milk is the resplendent white island There are human beings devoted to Narayana who are as bright as the moon
Those devotees attained to the Supreme Person in the state of solitude. They enter into the eternal God of a thousand flames.
They were devoid of senses, without food, without vibration, and without fragrance. Those lonely men inhabiting the White Island. O ascetics go there My Self has been revealed to me
Then we all heard the disembodied voice. They reached that place by the route as described
Having reached the white continent our minds were eager to see it Then the object of our gaze was thwarted
And we do not see the man, our sights taken away by that splendour. Then knowledge born of the Yoga of the gods appeared to us.
It cannot be easily seen by the scorching heat of the fortress. Then again after performing great austerities for a hundred years At the end of the vow we saw auspicious men
They were white and radiant like the Moon and were marked with all kinds of signs facing east and north, chanting the Brahman with daily folded hands.
That chanting called Manasa is chanted by those great souls. The Lord is pleased with your single-mindedness.
O tiger among ascetics the radiance of the Sun at the end of the yuga The brightness of each of the human beings was similar
We thought that the island was the abode of splendor None of them were greater than he, and they were all of equal splendour.
Then the radiance of a thousand suns rose simultaneously Suddenly we saw Jupiter again
Then all the men together rushed towards the messenger They folded their hands and shouted 'Om' with delight
Then we heard a loud noise as they spoke The sacrifice is offered to that god by the Tainaras.
We were suddenly distracted by his effulgence With our eyes and senses destroyed we cannot see anything
A single sound uttered by unequal men was heard widely Victory to you, lotus-eyed, O creator of the universe, I salute you.
O Hrishikesha, the ancestor of the great souls, I offer my obeisances unto Thee. We heard this sound accompanied by the letter of instruction
In the meantime the air is pure carrying all fragrances He carried divine flowers and herbs for the rituals
The lonely monkeys who know the five times are dear to him Then by the mind, speech and actions endowed with supreme devotion.
Surely the god has arrived there just as they had said We cannot see him, bewildered by his illusion.
When the wind ceased and the forces were restored O best of the Angirasas we became overwhelmed with anxiety
Among those thousands of human beings of pure birth No one worshiped us with their minds or eyes
Those hosts of ascetics also remained in their own state and followed the oneness of mind They did not impart to us the feeling of being Brahman.
Then we were very tired and exhausted from austerities He said something healthy being there incorporeal.
The god said You have seen white men devoid of all senses O Lord of the gods he is seen by these best of brahmins who have seen him
All ascetics go back as soon as you have come That God cannot be seen by a devotee in any way.
At length he attained solitude at will It is possible to see that venerable Rama orb of rays O best of brahmins you must perform a great task
Even after the past Kritayuga and the reverse. The brahmins reached the Tretayuga during the interval of Vaivasvata You will be helping the gods to accomplish their task
Then I heard those wonderful words which were like nectar By his grace we have easily reached the desired place
Thus by great austerities and also by offerings of oblations and poems How can you see a god whom we have not seen
Narayana is the great being, the creator of the universe, the enjoyer of the sacrifices. He is eternally immortal, unmanifest, worshiped by gods and demons.
Thus by one statement and by two or three opinions. Persuaded by the members Brihaspati was generous Then he completed the sacrifice and worshiped the god
After the sacrifice was completed king Vasu also ruled the people By the curse of Brahma he fell from heaven and entered the earth
O tiger among kings that king was devoted to truth and righteousness He was always devoted to righteousness and lived in the underworld
Being devoted to Narayana, chanting the mantra of Narayana. By the grace of Rama he got up again
He went from the earth to the place next to Brahma. That he has attained the supreme state is easily faithful.
Vaishampayana said But he was in despair and always accompanied by sorrow. The carrier of offerings approached the grandfather in a rage
And he reported all that to the Brahman in accordance with the law. After thinking for a moment the venerable Rama said
O sinless one I have seen a way to burn you Forgive me for a while Then you will be burnt O fire
Then Nara and Narayana will help you in the future O carrier of offerings you will burn the fire along with them both
The fire replied to the Brahman, "Let it be so. The sage Nara and Narayana knew that they were both born O king the words of that great time are the words of Svayambhuva Remembering his grandfather he went away again
Then Brahma said, "O fire, you shall be burnt. Today the lord of Sachi is looking at the fire of Khandava
Nara and Narayana, the two former gods of Vibhavas. They have arrived in this world for the purpose of performing the duties of the celestials
Arjuna and Vasudeva, whom the world admires. Bring them both together near Khandava Ask them both for help in burning Khandava Then you will burn that fire protected even by the gods
But both of them will try to stop all the creatures. I have no doubt that you will be with the king of the gods
On hearing one word the carrier of the oblations hastened Why did he approach Krishna and Arjuna and address them O tiger among kings he spoke words appropriate to the time Let us offer Khandava the fire of Satakrata who is unwilling. I have already told you that, O best of kings. On hearing the words of your fire the terrible fire burned
Arjuna said: I have excellent weapons, divine and many. With them I can fight even many thunderbolts.
O venerable one I have no bow equal to the strength of my arms The speed with which I could withstand the effort I was making in battle
And with arrows my meaning is quickly destroyed by many inexhaustible ones. The chariot is not capable of carrying my arrows as desired
And the horses of the divine unwanted, white, wind-swept. The chariot resounded like clouds and shone like the Sun
Thus there is no weapon equal to the prowess of Krishna. By which Madhava can kill serpents and devils in battle
You should tell me, O venerable one, the means and the accomplishment of action. How can I stop Indra from raining in the great forest
But whatever is done by man, the doers are their own fire. O venerable one you should bestow on me whatever you are capable of doing
Markandeya said While he was going king Husha surrounded by the citizens of the kingdom approached a brahmin and said 'O king I shall beg alms for the sake of my spiritual master at the appointed time'
The king said 'Let the venerable one tell me the time'
The Brahmin said: A man, being asked of the earth, should commit the greatest hatred in the world of living beings. O king I ask you how you can give him to me today
The king said: And let him not recite it today, for I have given him an unsolicited purpose, and I do not listen to him. Having promised to obtain the object and having given it I am very happy
I shall give you a thousand rohinis for my dear brahmin is begging you My mind does not get angry when I ask for what I have given I never grieve for anything
Having said this the king gave a thousand cows to the brahmin A brahmin obtained a thousand cows
Brihadasva said: After a month, O Arjuna, Naishadha invited Bhima. He left the city with a small family and went to Nishadha
A single white chariot with sixteen teeth. Fifty horses and six hundred infantrymen The king hurried off as if shaking the earth Then the highminded Ravana entered the city at once in a rage
Then Nala son of Veerasena reached Pushkara I have earned a lot of wealth and said to the divine lady again Damayanti and whatever else I have. O Pushkara this is my renunciation of your kingdom I am determined to resume gambling We bet our lives with one hand May you prosper
Conquering and taking the property of others, whether it be the kingdom or the wealth. It is said that the reward should be given in return
If you do not wish to engage in war gambling O king may there be peace between you and me with two chariots
This kingdom which is the food of the dynasty should be demanded in any way By whatever means the elderly are commanded to do so
Decide on one of the two today, Pushkar. Let the bow be named in the battle with Kaitava or in Akshavati
Addressed thus by Naishadha Pushkara smiling considering his victory as certain
Fortunately you have earned the wealth to pay back, Naishadha. Fortunately Damayanti's evil deeds have been annihilated
"O mightyarmed king fortunately you are holding on to your wife today Bhimi was adorned with the wealth she had conquered Obviously the gods will approach me like Indra in heaven O Naishadha I remember you daily even while waiting
Love is not with groups of friends. Today you have conquered the irreproachable Damayanti of beautiful hips I shall be accomplished for she is always in my heart
On hearing those words of Rama the king was in a state of confusion This is Nala angry with a sword to cut off his head King Nala whose eyes turned red with anger smiled and said to him
What are you talking about, Panava? You won't talk about winning. Then the gambling of Pushkara and Nala began He was defeated by the brave Lane with one hand He was sold for his life by heaps of gems
Having conquered Pushkara the king said with a smile This whole kingdom of mine is secure and thorns are destroyed Vaidarbhi you cannot look at the king's palace Fool you and your family have become her slaves
You have not done the deed that conquered me in the past That action was taken by Kali and you, the fool, do not realize it.
I will never blame you for what others have done. Live happily I shall give up your life
In the same way I shall distribute to you my share of all the provisions O valiant one there is no doubt that you will do the same for me
And my friendship will never leave you. Pushkara you are indeed my brother live a hundred years in autumn
Thus Nala whose prowess was true consoled his brother Embracing him again and again he sent him to his city
Consoled by Naishadha he replied to Pushkara in this way O King then he paid obeisance to the holy sage with folded palms May your fame be inexhaustible and live a hundred years happily. O king you are bestowing on me my life and my abode
O king he was thus honored by the king for a month Surrounded by his relatives Pushkara returned to his city in delight The saintly ones were accompanied by a large army and humble attendants O best among men he looked like the Sun shining with his body
The king sent Pushkara away wealthy and healthy The illustrious Rama entered the exceedingly splendid city
The king of Nishadha entered the city and congratulated the citizens The inhabitants of the villages with their hairs on their bodies rejoiced
All the people, headed by the ministers, said with folded hands. Today, O king, we were satisfied in the city and in the countryside. Just as the gods returned to worship Indra
On hearing this Damayanti was deeply grieved and said Brihadasva Doubting Nala she said to Kesini
Go to Keshi and test your arm again. Notice his character while standing nearby saying
And when he does something, he's the reason for it, darling. She noticed the movements of the man who was moving about there
Even fire should not be given to Keshi by his restriction If he asks for water he should not be given it in any case in a hurry
Having considered all this you have reported to me the cause of what you have seen in the arms of destiny and humanity And whatever else you see, I'll tell you.
Thus addressed by Damayanti Kesini departed Hearing the limbs of the horse sacrifice he returned
She told Damayanti everything that had happened The cause she saw in her arms was divine and human
Keshini said firmly and purely I have never seen Bhanusha I have never seen or heard of Damayanti of that kind before
Having reached the shortest communication he does not bow down anywhere Seeing him she happily leaves him according to her association
Even in times of crisis there is a huge hole in it There were many kinds of food for the sake of the seasonal leaves The king sent meat in abundance There waterpots were arranged for his washing
Then he looked at the pots and they were full Then he washed himself and rested his arms on the ground He took a handful of grass and placed it on the sun Then all of a sudden the fire carriage of oblations ignited there
I came here in amazement to see that most wonderful thing I noticed another great wonder in that place
That he does not burn even when he touches the fire, O auspicious one. The messenger who was not deprived of his water carried by chanting
I have seen another very great wonder That he took the flowers and slowly rubbed them with his hands The flowers were crushed with his hands and nothing else. They are fragrant and delightful again Having seen these wonderful symbols I have come here as a messenger
Brihadasva said Damayanti on hearing the actions of the holy sage He thought that Nala had arrived and was informed of his actions
Suspicious she gestured again to her husband's arm Weeping she again addressed Kesini in a gentle voice Go back to the arm of the madman O future lady get meat from the great mouth quickly She went to the arm and pulled out the meat. She was very hot and hurried to please me immediately
Then Keshini gave it to Damayanti, O son of the Kurus. In the past that funeral pyre was often used for the meat cooked by Nala
Thinking Nala was the charioteer she cried out in great distress Then I felt great agitation and washed my face He sent the twins with Keshini, O Bharatha. Arjuna recognized Indrasena along with his brother Then the king ran to him and embraced him and brought him to his lap Bahuka reached his two sons who resembled the sons of the gods Overcome with great grief he cried out loudly Naishadha, however, showed the transformation again and again. At once leaving behind his two sons he said to Keshini
O gentle lady this is a similar pair of my sons On seeing him I suddenly shed tears
People often see you falling down because of the error of signals O gentle lady we are guests of the country go happily
Sanjaya said Then the mighty Lord entered the incomparable mansion of Arjuna. The lotuseyed Rama touched the water on the auspicious ground
